WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:06.474
JUDY SINGER: I'm Judy Singer.

00:00:06.474 --> 00:00:09.050
I'm the Senior Vice Provost
for Faculty Development

00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:12.860
and Diversity and I want to
welcome you all to this event

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:14.630
on how to write
an Op-Ed, getting

00:00:14.630 --> 00:00:18.890
your voice into the news media.

00:00:18.890 --> 00:00:21.550
I want to just make
a few framing remarks

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:25.000
before turning it over to the
moderator of this panel, Ann

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:26.810
Marie Lipinski.

00:00:26.810 --> 00:00:31.940
And in thinking about how
to help the faculty get

00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:34.580
their voice out into the world,
we've done a number of events

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:37.280
and this one happens to be the
second time we've done this--

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:39.170
it's particularly popular.

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:42.440
And when we planned
this event, we

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:45.980
were thinking that there are
people on the faculty who

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:47.900
are interested in
figuring out how

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:49.970
to reach a broader audience.

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:53.450
But I think the events
of the last month

00:00:53.450 --> 00:00:59.750
have really called to task the
need for people in academia,

00:00:59.750 --> 00:01:01.820
now more than ever, to
get their voices out,

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:04.280
regardless of where
they fall in the debate.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:07.010
I think there's
just a need for us

00:01:07.010 --> 00:01:10.130
to take the time that we
have spent in dedicating

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:12.950
our lives to the study
of particular subjects

00:01:12.950 --> 00:01:15.740
to think about speaking, not
just to our colleagues, which

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:17.720
is what we do as our
bread and butter,

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.150
but to a broader audience.

00:01:20.150 --> 00:01:23.480
And people in the room
have a lot to offer.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:26.000
I'm particularly
pleased with the breadth

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.740
of people who are here.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:31.250
We have people from various
different schools at Harvard,

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:33.050
various different disciplines.

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:35.344
We run the gamut
from, oftentimes,

00:01:35.344 --> 00:01:37.760
we get arts and humanities and
social science people here.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.330
We have science people, law,
business, public health--

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:42.400
range of fields--

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.330
and I think that's,
actually, terrific

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:47.420
because it represents the riches
that Harvard has to offer,

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:52.460
but also the kinds of voices
that the folks who are up here

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:54.705
are interested in hearing
from because you might not

00:01:54.705 --> 00:01:56.330
meet some of these
people in the course

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:59.190
of your everyday business.

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:01.730
The Op-Ed forum is
particularly interesting

00:02:01.730 --> 00:02:03.530
because it's a short form.

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:05.720
We're used to writing
in longer form

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:07.940
and I think one of
the things that you'll

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:10.759
hear from the panelists
is how to help

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:13.340
think about moving
from the long form

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:17.420
that we're comfortable
being with whether it's

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:19.790
an article which you don't
think of as a long form,

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:22.700
but to these people,
that's a long form,

00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:24.651
or even teaching a
class or a seminar

00:02:24.651 --> 00:02:26.150
where you've got
an hour, two hours,

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:30.020
three hours to give your views
versus 90 seconds on the radio.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:33.090
So the short form, I think,
is particularly attractive

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:38.180
and in thinking about how to
take the work that we produce

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:40.490
and make it more
accessible to people,

00:02:40.490 --> 00:02:43.250
but also for people
who are writing a book,

00:02:43.250 --> 00:02:46.140
one of my first pieces of
advice is why don't you

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:50.510
start with an Op-Ed because a
book is a very long commitment

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:52.970
and an Op-Ed is something
that's much more achievable

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:56.660
and I think that's some
of what you'll hear today.

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:59.570
The third part of
thinking about this event

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:02.600
is that it's actually quite
instrumental in nature.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:06.170
Our panelists are very
interested in establishing

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:09.050
relationships with
members of our faculty

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:11.720
who do have something to
say about issues of the day

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:15.080
or other kinds of topics that
would have a broader audience.

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:17.510
And I'm going to
end with an anecdote

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:21.740
that at the end of the event
that we did two years ago,

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.290
one of the people in the room,
who was a first year assistant

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:28.070
professor, went up
to Trish Hall who

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:31.340
was Jim Dao's predecessor
at the New York Times

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:33.020
and pitched an idea.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:36.110
And three weeks later,
she had the lead Op-Ed

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:37.880
in the New York Times.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:42.170
So that gave me great pleasure
to see the kind of instrumental

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:42.950
nature of that.

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:47.000
So I'm hoping for a
repeat and maybe a repeat

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.100
across some other news outlets.

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:50.780
So with those
framing remarks, I am

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:53.780
going to turn the
moderator role over

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:57.606
to Ann Marie Lipinski who
is the curator of the Nieman

00:03:57.606 --> 00:04:00.230
Foundation for Journalism, which
is here at Harvard University.

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:02.960
It's a wonderful resource that
we have here and, in fact,

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:05.270
there are lots of
journalists at Nieman

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:07.580
who potentially could
also be helpful as you're

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:09.350
thinking about this role.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:11.540
She also, before
she came to Harvard,

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:13.630
was the editor in chief
of the Chicago Tribune

00:04:13.630 --> 00:04:15.680
and is a Pulitzer
Prize winner herself.

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:19.790
So she has been both
in the publishing end

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:21.950
and also now with
many years here

00:04:21.950 --> 00:04:24.860
at Harvard and time as also
with the University of Chicago,

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:26.540
also understands
the academic end

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:28.040
and I think it's
in a great position

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:29.760
to bridge these two worlds.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:32.092
So let me turn it
over to Ann Marie.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:40.580
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
Thank you so much, Judy.

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:45.680
Judy has very happily
made me her co-conspirator

00:04:45.680 --> 00:04:50.120
on a couple of initiatives here
at Harvard bringing faculty

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:52.500
and journalists together.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:54.950
And I am always
delighted to play

00:04:54.950 --> 00:04:57.230
that role for her and with her.

00:04:57.230 --> 00:05:03.530
So thank you for giving me the
chance to do that again today.

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:08.300
When she first reached out to
me to see if this was possible

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:12.780
today, it was many months
before the election.

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:17.720
And I think, certainly, my
views and maybe your views

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:22.760
of the value or lack thereof of
opinion journalism or opinion

00:05:22.760 --> 00:05:30.110
writing have maybe changed some.

00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:32.690
But I want to make sure--

00:05:32.690 --> 00:05:37.111
so Op-Ed-- the term comes
from opposite editorials.

00:05:37.111 --> 00:05:37.610
Right?

00:05:37.610 --> 00:05:39.080
That's what it
means, but I think

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:44.750
the op is often misused
to just focus on opinion.

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:48.050
It's also the first two
letters of that word.

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:52.190
And I think what you'll find
with the group of people

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:56.330
we are talking with today,
the world is awash in opinion

00:05:56.330 --> 00:05:59.400
and you can publish
it anywhere you want.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:02.810
You can publish your columns
on medium, you can publish,

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:06.630
you can tweet, you can
post them on Facebook,

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.410
you probably are members
of small Facebook groups

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:11.300
or Google Groups
or Google Hangouts

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:18.830
or any number of select cohorts
you make yourself a part of

00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:23.180
and you can talk with them and
share your opinions with them

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:24.290
at ease.

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:28.280
The difference between that
and what our colleagues today

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:30.650
are going to talk
about is really

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:36.200
reaching an audience outside
of that bubble and the accent

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:43.700
not necessarily on opinion,
but on information,

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:49.040
on expertise, and on
sharing that expertise

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:51.200
in a sophisticated
way with a broader

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:57.830
audience than, perhaps, many
of you are used to speaking to

00:06:57.830 --> 00:06:59.610
or with.

00:06:59.610 --> 00:07:04.190
And the value to us as
journalists is tremendous.

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:08.480
The ability of somebody with
an expertise about a subject

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.900
to be able to express that
to people beyond their ken

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:16.940
is incredibly valuable
in a democracy and just

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:19.610
to us individually
as people who are

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:21.950
very interested in
your work, but maybe

00:07:21.950 --> 00:07:24.660
can't always understand it.

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:27.110
And so I think there's sometimes
this divide between what

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:31.580
journalism does and
what the academy does

00:07:31.580 --> 00:07:35.060
and, hopefully, at the end
of our time here together,

00:07:35.060 --> 00:07:44.030
that will be demystified for you
and also some for our panelists

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:47.060
whose backgrounds,
with one exception,

00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:49.610
are on the journalism side.

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:53.840
As Judy said, we saw this become
very successful the first time

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:57.350
she hosted such a conversation
and, hopefully, that

00:07:57.350 --> 00:08:00.350
will be the same for today.

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:03.380
So I was, yesterday
and today, just

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:07.430
looking at kind of recent
examples of the kinds of things

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:11.000
that our three journalists
here today think

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:18.710
about or have chosen as opinion
pieces or Op-Ed pieces to use.

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:22.220
And so James, in
the last day or so,

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:26.390
has overseen the publication
of a piece in the New York

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:30.620
Times written by a Cuban
born American who's

00:08:30.620 --> 00:08:35.720
writing about her reactions
to Castro's death and the kind

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:38.870
of haunting presence
he had in her life

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:42.820
really from the time
she was cognizant.

00:08:42.820 --> 00:08:46.160
A freshmen from New
York University writing

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:47.685
about the animosity that--

00:08:47.685 --> 00:08:49.060
I'm not sure if
it's a he or she,

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:50.495
there were initials
only in the piece--

00:08:50.495 --> 00:08:50.780
JAMES DAO: It's a she.

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:53.480
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: She-- that
she has experienced as somebody

00:08:53.480 --> 00:08:58.040
who is a Trump supporter.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:01.100
A piece about how
the FCC is going

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:05.750
to auction off a chunk of the
public airwaves and an argument

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:08.690
that the writer makes for using
the proceeds from that to build

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:13.790
a 21st century infrastructure
of public interest media

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:17.720
written by the president
of a foundation.

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:19.280
In the Globe "Ideas"
section, there

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:22.160
was a piece about
our complicated views

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:27.320
about nature and how we think
about alien species invading

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:30.950
our habitats, and
examination of the labor

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:32.540
movement in the age of Trump.

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:38.620
We've all certainly
heard the term Alt-Right.

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:41.110
I've not heard
the term Alt-Labor

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:43.120
so I learned about
Alt-Labor through that piece

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:49.180
and it's a new approach
to pro-worker activism.

00:09:49.180 --> 00:09:53.170
And over a cognoscente
at WBUR, there

00:09:53.170 --> 00:09:57.430
was a piece about speaking up
for undocumented workers who

00:09:57.430 --> 00:10:00.280
you may work with yourself.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:03.610
And also, one that was
very relevant to many of us

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:07.030
last week, how to go home
and deal with your family

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:10.870
after the election
at Thanksgiving.

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:15.820
So that's a huge range
of ideas and thoughts

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:19.975
and expertise represented just
really over the course of 24

00:10:19.975 --> 00:10:23.760
or 48 hours on these three--

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:28.330
in two publications
and one radio station.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:35.530
But I wanted to start with Naomi
and with that as a backdrop,

00:10:35.530 --> 00:10:40.450
because Naomi is somebody
who has navigated

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:44.650
both waters, if we want to
think of them as separate ponds.

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:48.340
So she is somebody who has
written for the Washington

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:50.950
Post and the LA Times and
Nature and Science and The New

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:53.380
Statesman and on and on.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:56.380
She's worked in the print,
she's worked in video,

00:10:56.380 --> 00:11:00.010
she's written books, she's
written Op-Eds for newspapers,

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:02.890
for magazines, she's
done a TED Talk,

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:04.970
she's worked on a documentary.

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:09.910
So on the one hand, she's
very skilled at the popular.

00:11:09.910 --> 00:11:12.220
Here are just two headlines--

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:14.020
one from a piece and
one from a book--

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:17.560
The Pope and the Planet--
we'd all read that--

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:20.740
Merchants of Doubt--
we all read that--

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:24.000
and then, maybe the
not so popular culture,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.050
here's the title of one, The
Rejection of Continental Drift:

00:11:29.050 --> 00:11:32.290
Theory and Method in
American Earth Science--

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:36.260
probably not something any
of these three would publish.

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:38.056
JAMES DAO: Maybe with
a different headline.

00:11:38.056 --> 00:11:40.222
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Maybe
with a different headline.

00:11:40.222 --> 00:11:42.430
And that's a key, actually,
what Jim just said.

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:49.360
And so I want to see if we can
learn from Naomi how she thinks

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:52.900
about those as very
separate disciplines,

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:57.630
but rising from the same well
of knowledge and expertise

00:11:57.630 --> 00:11:59.110
that you bring to both.

00:11:59.110 --> 00:12:04.180
So talk about coming at popular
pieces, popular culture pieces,

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:08.350
or publications in
the popular culture

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:09.737
with your academic background.

00:12:09.737 --> 00:12:10.570
NAOMI ORESKES: Sure.

00:12:10.570 --> 00:12:10.840
OK.

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:11.320
Thanks.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:13.528
Well, thanks very much for
having me here and thanks,

00:12:13.528 --> 00:12:15.384
Judy, for organizing
this and, Liz,

00:12:15.384 --> 00:12:17.800
I have to say I do feel kind
of a weight of responsibility

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:21.320
being the token
academic on this panel.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:23.180
So I guess the
best place to start

00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:25.180
is just by saying I don't
think of them as being

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:26.320
separate ponds.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:29.090
I've never thought of
the diverse work I do.

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:31.090
I work in science, I work
in history of science,

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:34.030
I work in what you
call the popular realm.

00:12:34.030 --> 00:12:35.710
I never think of
them and I never

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:38.350
have thought of them as
different projects and that's

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:40.660
something that deans and
chairs have not always

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:42.590
understood, although
I think they do now,

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:44.560
and I'm in a very
nice place now where

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:47.830
now I get to be trotted
out as an exemplar of how

00:12:47.830 --> 00:12:50.530
this can be done, but it
wasn't always that way.

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:52.360
So the first thing
you have to realize

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:56.770
is that I think you have to have
a conception of what you think

00:12:56.770 --> 00:13:00.010
your project is and I guess
being an earth scientist,

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:01.510
for me, the metaphor
I've always had

00:13:01.510 --> 00:13:04.271
is kind of the iceberg metaphor
that what I do in public

00:13:04.271 --> 00:13:05.770
is a kind of the
tip of the iceberg.

00:13:05.770 --> 00:13:08.740
It's the small piece that
stands out that people see,

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:11.310
people like yourself
or these folks,

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:14.620
but it's supported by this
giant mass of material

00:13:14.620 --> 00:13:17.650
beneath the surface that
most of you don't see,

00:13:17.650 --> 00:13:19.270
but that's the
part that supports

00:13:19.270 --> 00:13:21.520
it, that's the part that
the upper part floats on.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:25.391
And so all of you, as academics,
have that mass of work

00:13:25.391 --> 00:13:27.640
that you've done that you've
worked incredibly hard on

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:30.190
or you've spent long
hours in the archives

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:33.550
or in the laboratory or in the
field or wherever you work.

00:13:33.550 --> 00:13:36.670
And you have all this stuff at
your disposal that you can use.

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:38.680
And so I think that's
the starting point

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:41.417
is a sense of empowerment
based on your knowledge

00:13:41.417 --> 00:13:43.000
and the knowledge
you have that if you

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.610
start to write about something
based on your research,

00:13:46.610 --> 00:13:49.240
you know more about that
than probably anybody.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:50.000
Right?

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.410
And so that's, I think, where
my public work comes from

00:13:53.410 --> 00:13:56.680
is out of this
body, this big body,

00:13:56.680 --> 00:14:00.010
of detailed work and long
hours spent in dusty archives

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:01.960
which Gabriella knows about.

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:03.300
Right?

00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:04.750
So I thought,
maybe, I could just

00:14:04.750 --> 00:14:07.180
say something of how I
wrote my first Op-Ed piece

00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:10.350
because that's the other
second really important thing.

00:14:10.350 --> 00:14:12.684
And I don't think the folks
on this panel will disagree,

00:14:12.684 --> 00:14:14.933
but they may have a slightly
different view, because I

00:14:14.933 --> 00:14:17.650
know sometimes editors work
with academics to figure out

00:14:17.650 --> 00:14:19.240
what they might
want to write about,

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:22.104
but that's not how I came
to write my first Op-Ed.

00:14:22.104 --> 00:14:23.770
I came to write my
first Op-Ed because I

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:25.430
had something I wanted to say.

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:28.922
And I think that's the
bottom line for anyone is,

00:14:28.922 --> 00:14:30.130
do you have something to say?

00:14:30.130 --> 00:14:32.860
If you don't, then as the
great sage Tom Lehrer said,

00:14:32.860 --> 00:14:34.370
the least you can do is shut up.

00:14:34.370 --> 00:14:37.390
So don't talk until you
have something to say,

00:14:37.390 --> 00:14:39.460
but when you do,
that's the moment.

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:42.870
And so I think the key thing
is to sort of be aware,

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:45.240
to kind of go through the
world with an awareness of how

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:47.430
your work might
connect to something.

00:14:47.430 --> 00:14:50.190
And when that moment
occurs, that's when you act.

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:54.450
And so some years ago,
more than 10 years ago, we

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:56.674
had some terrible wildfires
in Southern California

00:14:56.674 --> 00:14:58.590
and my children were out
of school for a week.

00:14:58.590 --> 00:15:00.540
We had a fire week.

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:03.300
Here we have snow days, but in
California, we have fire days.

00:15:03.300 --> 00:15:07.130
And it was a quite traumatic
time in Southern California.

00:15:07.130 --> 00:15:09.480
Lots of people were
displaced from their homes.

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:10.542
And my children and I--

00:15:10.542 --> 00:15:12.000
and you couldn't
really go anywhere

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.100
because it was so
much smoke and dust.

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:16.590
It was not safe to be outside.

00:15:16.590 --> 00:15:19.410
After three days of baking
cookies and things like that,

00:15:19.410 --> 00:15:20.720
and I'm reading the papers--

00:15:20.720 --> 00:15:22.095
and this is the
other thing, too,

00:15:22.095 --> 00:15:23.910
is noticing what's
not being said.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:26.670
So there were all these things
being written about the fires

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:28.170
and no one was
making the connection

00:15:28.170 --> 00:15:30.450
to climate change, no one.

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.570
And I, personally, think that
of all the different things

00:15:33.570 --> 00:15:36.120
that climate change does,
is already doing, and will

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:39.120
do to us, at least, if
you live in the west,

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:41.250
fires are the most important
thing because they're

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:43.050
really, really scary.

00:15:43.050 --> 00:15:44.426
People are afraid
of fire, people

00:15:44.426 --> 00:15:46.883
get it that fires destroy their
homes and their communities

00:15:46.883 --> 00:15:49.440
and their lives and cost
billions of dollars in damage.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:51.990
So fires connect climate
change to people's lives

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:55.395
in very real, tangible, and
emotionally present way.

00:15:55.395 --> 00:15:57.020
And so I just wrote
something about it.

00:15:57.020 --> 00:16:01.190
I wrote, basically,
something that said, guys,

00:16:01.190 --> 00:16:02.820
you know climate change.

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:05.460
And I sent it over the transom
to the Los Angeles Times--

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:06.760
didn't know anybody.

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:08.880
And an editor there
saw it and liked it

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:11.400
and called me up and said,
we'd like to run with this.

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:13.530
And then over the next 24
hours, we worked together

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:15.900
to clean it up and
I learned a lot

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:20.430
working with an editor about
how to write a good Op-Ed piece.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:23.100
You learn by working
with editors.

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:26.130
So after that experience,
then I realized, OK, this

00:16:26.130 --> 00:16:27.610
is actually not that hard.

00:16:27.610 --> 00:16:30.245
I mean it's different,
like I was just saying,

00:16:30.245 --> 00:16:32.370
I mean the style of an
Op-Ed is different than what

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:33.960
we're used to in academic life.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:37.190
You have to hit it hard, don't
bury the lead, main idea up

00:16:37.190 --> 00:16:42.090
front, only one idea, not
17, no table of contents,

00:16:42.090 --> 00:16:44.405
no footnotes, almost
no references--

00:16:44.405 --> 00:16:46.530
and if they already have
to kind of explore-- well,

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:48.460
I guess now with
hyperlinks, you kind of do.

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:48.900
JAMES DAO: That's right.

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:50.670
NAOMI ORESKES: My first
Op-Ed was in the days before

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:51.550
a hyperlink--

00:16:51.550 --> 00:16:53.790
I mean old fashioned
print-- all that kind thing.

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:56.520
So anyway, the point is
I had something to say

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:58.410
and I said it and
somebody was interested

00:16:58.410 --> 00:17:00.190
and then things went from there.

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:03.780
So there's not really
like a magic trick

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:05.579
about writing an
Op-Ed, but you do

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:10.200
have to let go of a lot
of your academic concern

00:17:10.200 --> 00:17:12.930
with detail, nuance, subtlety.

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:15.329
The art of an Op-Ed
piece, subtlety

00:17:15.329 --> 00:17:17.940
is not kind of like
job one, although there

00:17:17.940 --> 00:17:19.230
is a place for it at times.

00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:22.240
It's not to say that the best
Op-Ed pieces is a sledgehammer,

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:23.160
it's not.

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:26.730
But it's just we've been so
trained to focus as academics

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.460
on the subtlety, the
nuance, the details,

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:31.560
and so you do have
to let go of some

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:34.530
of your academic sensibilities.

00:17:34.530 --> 00:17:36.570
If you can find
someone to work with,

00:17:36.570 --> 00:17:39.680
that's a really good thing,
but my initial Op-Eds were just

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.476
on my own, but I
was very lucky--

00:17:42.476 --> 00:17:44.850
and this is something I think
we could do here at Harvard

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:47.183
and I'd actually like talk
to you more about this later.

00:17:47.183 --> 00:17:49.320
So after I wrote my
first Op-Ed piece,

00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:51.480
then I got an email
from someone at UCSD.

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:53.910
I was teaching in San
Diego at the time--

00:17:53.910 --> 00:17:55.410
and just a small aside--

00:17:55.410 --> 00:17:57.510
when I was in San Diego,
the New York Times never

00:17:57.510 --> 00:18:00.060
accepted any of my Op-Ed
pieces, and then I moved here,

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:01.990
and suddenly like [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:04.980
So OK, better late than never.

00:18:04.980 --> 00:18:05.970
I know it wasn't me.

00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:12.630
But I got an email from someone
in our press and communication

00:18:12.630 --> 00:18:15.180
office and she said, that was
a great piece, I loved it,

00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:17.560
would you like to work
with me in the future?

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:20.174
And so, we did and we
had a great partnership

00:18:20.174 --> 00:18:21.090
and it went like this.

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:23.010
I had something to say,
something happened,

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:24.900
I would write a draft,
I sent it to her--

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:26.389
Inga Kiddera was her name.

00:18:26.389 --> 00:18:28.680
Inga would look at it, she'd
give me some suggestions--

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.830
she had been in journalism--

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:33.840
I would make them, and then she
would shop them around for me.

00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:36.540
And that was a giant blessing
because, frankly, it's

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.880
hard to shop your
own Op-Ed pieces.

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:44.425
And nobody likes rejection,
but it's particularly--

00:18:44.425 --> 00:18:46.800
if you're an academic and
you're used to getting reviews,

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:48.780
you get feedback, you
revise, you resubmit--

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:51.077
to have an Op-Ed
editor to say, sorry,

00:18:51.077 --> 00:18:53.160
we're not interested and
no explanation, nothing--

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.990
because that's how it goes
because they're not obligation

00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:55.620
to give--

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:57.990
they're not reviewers, right?

00:18:57.990 --> 00:19:00.360
That was kind of hard, but
she would shop them for me.

00:19:00.360 --> 00:19:04.920
And so working with Inga, we'd
place pieces, as Tara said,

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:08.130
Washington Post, Chicago
Tribune, Los Angeles Times,

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:09.720
San Francisco
Chronicle-- practically

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:11.261
every major newspaper
in this country

00:19:11.261 --> 00:19:14.019
with the notable exception of
one in New York, but that's OK.

00:19:14.019 --> 00:19:15.810
And here's the other
really important thing

00:19:15.810 --> 00:19:17.910
I just want to say before
I pass on to the others.

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:23.246
So one thing I've really noticed
moving here from California--

00:19:23.246 --> 00:19:24.912
it's not a criticism
of Harvard which is

00:19:24.912 --> 00:19:26.203
an incredibly great university.

00:19:26.203 --> 00:19:28.020
I'm totally proud and
thrilled to be here,

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:32.737
but we tend to sort of think
when we think about newspapers,

00:19:32.737 --> 00:19:35.070
the media, we think about The
New York Times, The Boston

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:36.360
Globe, and that's fine.

00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:39.020
They're absolutely
fantastic, amazing newspapers

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:41.282
and they reach lots
and lots of people.

00:19:41.282 --> 00:19:42.740
But there are
millions and millions

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:44.990
of people in this country
who do not read The New York

00:19:44.990 --> 00:19:48.170
Times and that could be hard
to believe being at Harvard--

00:19:48.170 --> 00:19:50.900
or The Boston Globe or
even The Los Angeles Times.

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:54.530
There's this world of people are
out there that we don't reach

00:19:54.530 --> 00:19:57.860
and this election has made
that incredibly clear,

00:19:57.860 --> 00:19:59.610
if we didn't know it beforehand.

00:19:59.610 --> 00:20:01.750
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: So
thank you for that, Naomi,

00:20:01.750 --> 00:20:04.520
and I wanted to turn to Katie.

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:08.060
So Naomi said something
very, very important.

00:20:08.060 --> 00:20:10.380
She said she's home,
she's baking cookies,

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:13.430
there are fires all around
her, she had this idea

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:15.410
that fires connect
people to climate

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:17.540
change in a very real way.

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:19.970
And so embedded in
that observation

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:22.820
is that this was
incredibly timely.

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:25.760
The wolf was at the
door, she had knowledge,

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:28.460
and she jumped on
it very quickly.

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:30.830
There was a reason
for an editor to look

00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:33.170
at that piece in that moment.

00:20:33.170 --> 00:20:35.750
And I'm wondering
if you can talk

00:20:35.750 --> 00:20:40.580
about the importance of
that, Katie, and conversely,

00:20:40.580 --> 00:20:46.730
getting an idea, a
pitch, that's kind of--

00:20:46.730 --> 00:20:48.710
it could happen
any day of the year

00:20:48.710 --> 00:20:51.350
and there's not that sense
of urgency or timeliness

00:20:51.350 --> 00:20:53.930
and how you think about
those two in different ways.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:54.971
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Sure.

00:20:54.971 --> 00:20:57.680
I can't overemphasize the
importance of timeliness.

00:20:57.680 --> 00:20:59.210
If something is
happening, that's

00:20:59.210 --> 00:21:02.990
when you should be contacting
an editor, not three days later.

00:21:02.990 --> 00:21:06.620
I often, when I was
the Ideas editor,

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:13.010
would get a pitch about a topic
that was very, very important,

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:16.820
but not in the news
anymore and there was not

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:19.910
a lot of reason to start
talking about it again.

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:23.030
So within minutes of
something happening

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:25.179
is when you should be
reaching out to an editor,

00:21:25.179 --> 00:21:26.720
when you should be
thinking about it.

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:29.330
So that talks a
lot to what Naomi

00:21:29.330 --> 00:21:31.707
said which is always be
thinking about these things,

00:21:31.707 --> 00:21:33.290
always be thinking
about what you have

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:36.260
to say on different topics
and areas of expertise

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:39.350
that you have so that
you can jump on it.

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:42.920
And I would, actually,
say the other good thing

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:45.800
to do is just talk
to editors in advance

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:48.020
and get to know editors,
have coffee with them.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:52.910
I know I often would
make appointments

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:58.040
with academics or
other local voices

00:21:58.040 --> 00:22:02.420
that we wanted to, someday,
have as contributors

00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:06.350
thinking about--

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:09.470
often, ideas would come
through just a conversation

00:22:09.470 --> 00:22:12.330
and someone would say,
I'm working on this topic

00:22:12.330 --> 00:22:16.130
and I have a lot of research
on x and we would figure out

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:16.892
an angle together.

00:22:16.892 --> 00:22:19.100
And that was one of the
things that I actually really

00:22:19.100 --> 00:22:23.180
enjoyed about working with
Op-Eds is the idea that I could

00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:25.100
help the person think
through what they

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:27.100
were trying to say on a topic.

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:31.040
It doesn't need to be a
700 word Op-Ed fully formed

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:32.510
when you turn it in.

00:22:32.510 --> 00:22:35.000
It can be a nugget of an idea
that we can work together

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.114
to form into a piece.

00:22:38.114 --> 00:22:39.530
The counter side
to that, the idea

00:22:39.530 --> 00:22:41.120
that you have something
that could work any day,

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:43.100
it's often what works
is something that's

00:22:43.100 --> 00:22:47.020
counter-intuitive so
something that breaks

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:53.330
the stereotypes around a
topic or that is interesting,

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:57.110
unique research that only you
are working on in that moment

00:22:57.110 --> 00:23:01.860
or that only you are talking
about that will change

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:03.110
a reader's mind, for instance.

00:23:06.290 --> 00:23:08.212
I always say, why are
we doing this piece now

00:23:08.212 --> 00:23:09.920
is one of the questions
that I frequently

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:14.990
ask people who are
pitching Op-Eds to me

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:17.900
and kind of making sure that
when you're first approaching

00:23:17.900 --> 00:23:19.489
the editor, that
you can say this is

00:23:19.489 --> 00:23:20.780
why we're doing this piece now.

00:23:20.780 --> 00:23:23.750
It's because this is a brand
new piece of research or this

00:23:23.750 --> 00:23:26.630
is something that's on the
news or this is something

00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:30.410
that only I can
bring this expertise

00:23:30.410 --> 00:23:33.230
and the topic is extremely
relevant to your readers

00:23:33.230 --> 00:23:34.462
because--

00:23:34.462 --> 00:23:35.920
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
Can you, Katie,

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:40.550
so because you're The Boston
Globe and you sit in this--

00:23:40.550 --> 00:23:43.950
you're awash in
academic institutions

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:47.390
and real and potential
contributors,

00:23:47.390 --> 00:23:50.450
do you have any observations
about or maybe an example

00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:57.110
of a really successful and also
maybe a less than successful

00:23:57.110 --> 00:23:59.060
pitch that you've
had about something

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:02.960
related to academic
research and feels right

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:04.280
or does not in the moment?

00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:05.321
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Sure.

00:24:05.321 --> 00:24:06.590
I think that they're--

00:24:06.590 --> 00:24:09.173
all you have to do is read the
Sunday "Idea" section and you'd

00:24:09.173 --> 00:24:11.930
find successful
pitches from academics.

00:24:11.930 --> 00:24:17.600
We often have pieces,
but things that are--

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:19.100
I'm trying to think,
of course, I'm

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:23.210
struggling now that you've asked
me and put me on the spot--

00:24:23.210 --> 00:24:24.140
but we--

00:24:24.140 --> 00:24:26.300
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
I should say,

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:30.320
very excitedly and happily,
Katie's mind is in a new place.

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:35.060
Although she edited ideas and
Sunday Op-Eds for some time,

00:24:35.060 --> 00:24:37.940
she's the recently promoted
managing editor of The Boston

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:40.090
Globe so yea for Katie.

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:41.700
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Thank you.

00:24:41.700 --> 00:24:46.340
I would say that there
are great examples.

00:24:46.340 --> 00:24:48.800
We did a piece about
the history of the word

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:51.440
racism a couple of weeks ago.

00:24:51.440 --> 00:24:52.970
I didn't actually
edit that, but I

00:24:52.970 --> 00:24:57.020
was part of the initial process
of soliciting it and bringing

00:24:57.020 --> 00:24:57.770
it to The Globe.

00:24:57.770 --> 00:25:00.440
And it was one of
those pieces where

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:04.960
it could have been very
academic and jargony

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:06.980
and I know that there
was a lot of work

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:11.090
put into making it something
that a lay reader could read

00:25:11.090 --> 00:25:12.320
and get through--

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:14.870
early drafts were
sort of dense--

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:18.170
but the writer worked very
closely with the editor

00:25:18.170 --> 00:25:20.960
and made it something
that felt very accessible

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:22.850
to the average reader.

00:25:22.850 --> 00:25:26.360
I think that there are a couple
of pitfalls that writers often

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:29.310
find themselves in which
make things not successful.

00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:32.000
So for instance, what
I was saying earlier

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:35.330
was there's this
phenomenon called editing

00:25:35.330 --> 00:25:38.720
by committee in
which you will go

00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:41.421
through the first
edit with a writer

00:25:41.421 --> 00:25:43.670
and they will send you back
a note that says something

00:25:43.670 --> 00:25:45.620
to the effect of,
OK well, I just

00:25:45.620 --> 00:25:48.110
need to share this
around my department.

00:25:48.110 --> 00:25:50.030
That almost never
works for an editor

00:25:50.030 --> 00:25:54.230
because what comes
back from that process

00:25:54.230 --> 00:26:01.010
is a lot of caveats being
added to the piece when--

00:26:01.010 --> 00:26:03.140
Going back to
something Naomi said,

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:04.640
really what works
the best is when

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:07.220
you have a straight point
that you're trying to make

00:26:07.220 --> 00:26:09.470
and you're using
supporting evidence around

00:26:09.470 --> 00:26:13.130
that as opposed to something
that becomes muddied

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:15.680
because you want to make sure
that this person gets credit

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:21.260
for their research or a side
is added because you want

00:26:21.260 --> 00:26:23.030
to make sure it feels nuanced.

00:26:23.030 --> 00:26:24.920
Nuance is important
and, in fact, I

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:31.940
think people go too far in
terms of taking nuance out,

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:35.360
because I think often you do
want to have those caveats,

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:39.620
but you don't want to
have the caveats take away

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:42.280
from your argument and
that's often what can happen.

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:45.050
It's when you
start saying things

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:49.490
like I'm making this
really strident point,

00:26:49.490 --> 00:26:52.790
but there is all this research
that says the opposite.

00:26:55.780 --> 00:27:00.380
And I feel like there is
a pressure in academia

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:02.600
to make sure everyone
in your department

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:09.380
feels like they are in the
know about what you're writing

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:12.140
or about this excellent
opportunity you

00:27:12.140 --> 00:27:15.830
have to contribute to The
Boston Globe or et cetera.

00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:20.270
But when that process starts
to take away from the punch

00:27:20.270 --> 00:27:23.600
or impact that the
piece can have,

00:27:23.600 --> 00:27:26.540
that's when it gets in the way.

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:29.120
And so the other
thing that I always

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:31.850
appreciate, as I mentioned,
is when someone wants

00:27:31.850 --> 00:27:34.760
to credit their bosses' work.

00:27:34.760 --> 00:27:36.930
That happens all the time.

00:27:36.930 --> 00:27:40.730
It's constantly like--
and I want to say--

00:27:40.730 --> 00:27:42.680
in the drafts, obviously.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.440
This doesn't often ever
really make it into the paper,

00:27:45.440 --> 00:27:48.080
because that's one of the
first things, as an editor,

00:27:48.080 --> 00:27:50.570
that you take out, frankly.

00:27:50.570 --> 00:27:56.120
So you'll get a piece that's
like this Op-Ed wouldn't have

00:27:56.120 --> 00:28:00.410
been possible without
the previous research

00:28:00.410 --> 00:28:03.560
by my department chair.

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:08.450
So just know going in that
if you want to do that,

00:28:08.450 --> 00:28:09.786
you're going to be really--

00:28:09.786 --> 00:28:11.660
it's going to be hard
to find an editor who's

00:28:11.660 --> 00:28:13.880
going to let that
end up in the paper.

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:15.921
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: I'm
smiling because it's also

00:28:15.921 --> 00:28:18.920
completely antithetical to
what would happen in a newsroom

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:21.080
where reporters will never
give their bosses credit

00:28:21.080 --> 00:28:21.621
for anything.

00:28:21.621 --> 00:28:22.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:25.180
It's the precise
opposite, culturally.

00:28:25.180 --> 00:28:27.109
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Right.

00:28:27.109 --> 00:28:29.150
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: The
editors only ruin things.

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:31.344
Your bosses ruin your best work.

00:28:31.344 --> 00:28:32.510
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Exactly.

00:28:32.510 --> 00:28:35.330
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: One of the
great mysteries of the universe

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:39.620
is how the pieces get chosen for
The New York Times Op-Ed page.

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:46.730
You're in the really
fortunate position

00:28:46.730 --> 00:28:50.056
to be overwhelmed
with submissions.

00:28:50.056 --> 00:28:51.680
You're in the really
difficult position

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:54.290
of being overwhelmed
with submissions.

00:28:54.290 --> 00:28:59.690
So, Jim, can you just
talk about that process?

00:28:59.690 --> 00:29:04.130
So you're thinking about
tomorrow's page, what's

00:29:04.130 --> 00:29:07.550
been the run up to what
we will read there,

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:11.414
what will appear there--
in print or online.

00:29:11.414 --> 00:29:12.680
JAMES DAO: Sure.

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:15.138
I just want to say I've only
been there 10 months so I have

00:29:15.138 --> 00:29:16.484
yet to reject one of Naomi's.

00:29:16.484 --> 00:29:17.900
NAOMI ORESKES: But
it will happen.

00:29:20.697 --> 00:29:23.030
JAMES DAO: And it's true that
we don't give explanations

00:29:23.030 --> 00:29:26.270
because, as I explained to one
writer, if that's what we did,

00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:29.400
that's all we would do.

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:32.710
So I'd love to be
able to boil it down,

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:36.950
but it's, of course, it's
like a newsroom, in fact.

00:29:36.950 --> 00:29:39.460
It's sausage making
and it's sausage

00:29:39.460 --> 00:29:43.870
making as ugly as anything that
happens in the news operation.

00:29:43.870 --> 00:29:47.200
But I'll sort of run you
through a typical day

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:49.420
where we start with
the morning meeting.

00:29:49.420 --> 00:29:53.290
We all come in trying to have
read not just our paper, which

00:29:53.290 --> 00:29:56.230
is enough of an ordeal, but
has skimmed other papers

00:29:56.230 --> 00:29:58.510
and have a sense
of what's going on.

00:29:58.510 --> 00:30:03.150
And we discuss what is the
big story that we care about?

00:30:03.150 --> 00:30:05.650
What is the running story we're
going to continue to follow?

00:30:05.650 --> 00:30:11.065
And what is the role of
opinion in this process?

00:30:11.065 --> 00:30:13.660
And that, in and of itself, is
a really complicated question

00:30:13.660 --> 00:30:17.200
because opinion is so much
more diverse and broad

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:18.260
than it once was.

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:22.660
The Op-Ed page of The Times
historically was two pieces

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:25.750
and columnists and
it still is that--

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:27.779
two pieces by outside
writers, often academics,

00:30:27.779 --> 00:30:29.320
but they could be
novelists, it could

00:30:29.320 --> 00:30:34.520
be regular people, and then
two of our regular columnists.

00:30:34.520 --> 00:30:40.480
But today, we are now
online only essays.

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:44.080
We are the Sunday Review
which is 12 to 15 very

00:30:44.080 --> 00:30:46.840
often long style essays,
sometimes reported

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:49.930
and sometimes personal
narrative, sometimes

00:30:49.930 --> 00:30:54.640
standard opinionated Op-Eds with
a prescription and a problem.

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:56.680
We are the international
New York Times,

00:30:56.680 --> 00:31:01.780
which has its own group of
outside international writers

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:04.780
writing from across the globe.

00:31:04.780 --> 00:31:07.720
And there's a whole variety
of online types of pieces

00:31:07.720 --> 00:31:09.020
that we do.

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:10.420
One of our favorites
is something

00:31:10.420 --> 00:31:15.070
called The Stone which is a
philosopher's blog, basically.

00:31:15.070 --> 00:31:16.550
It's part of the
Op-Ed operation.

00:31:16.550 --> 00:31:19.970
Some of The Stone essays get
into the paper or the Sunday

00:31:19.970 --> 00:31:23.080
Review, but most of
them just live online

00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:25.870
and it has a
dedicated readership.

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:27.650
Maybe, if there's any
philosophers here,

00:31:27.650 --> 00:31:30.070
you've actually looked at it.

00:31:30.070 --> 00:31:33.860
And we have others like
that that are developing.

00:31:33.860 --> 00:31:39.700
So as Katie pointed
out, timeliness is huge.

00:31:39.700 --> 00:31:42.460
We're looking for pieces
that can go-- sometimes,

00:31:42.460 --> 00:31:46.210
we get Op-Eds within an hour
of an event taking place.

00:31:46.210 --> 00:31:47.682
And very often--

00:31:47.682 --> 00:31:50.140
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: And that's
when you should be pitching.

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:52.840
JAMES DAO: But very often,
they're astonishingly good

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:56.890
and we try not to
distinguish between what

00:31:56.890 --> 00:31:58.960
goes online versus
what goes in the paper

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:01.720
because, more and more, we
are purely online operation,

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:06.190
but we do give a little bit more
care and tending to the paper

00:32:06.190 --> 00:32:09.910
because the readers are a
little bit more careful there

00:32:09.910 --> 00:32:12.010
and we have more
time to work on them.

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:16.690
But we get full-fledged
850 word Op-Eds

00:32:16.690 --> 00:32:21.490
within an hour or two of major
events and if they are good,

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:24.610
we will put them online
as quickly as we can,

00:32:24.610 --> 00:32:26.355
sometimes within an
hour or two hours

00:32:26.355 --> 00:32:27.730
depending on the
quality of them.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:35.230
What I would say to sort of be
the counter voice on timeliness

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:38.320
is every clever reporter
has figured out,

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:40.840
over the course of their
career, that you can make

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:42.580
almost anything
feel timely if you

00:32:42.580 --> 00:32:44.750
have the right framing for it.

00:32:44.750 --> 00:32:47.890
And the key to anything,
whether it's a news story

00:32:47.890 --> 00:32:51.872
or whether it's an Op-Ed, is
that as Naomi points out very

00:32:51.872 --> 00:32:53.830
correctly, you should
write about what you know

00:32:53.830 --> 00:32:56.470
and what you care about.

00:32:56.470 --> 00:32:59.200
We receive 1,000 pictures
a day about people

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:00.760
who want to tell
us why Trump won

00:33:00.760 --> 00:33:03.850
and really, we don't care
almost from any of you.

00:33:03.850 --> 00:33:06.910
We have columnists, editorial
writers, and big brains

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:08.946
across the globe trying
to tell us what that is.

00:33:08.946 --> 00:33:10.570
We're probably not
going to really care

00:33:10.570 --> 00:33:12.514
about your opinion on that.

00:33:12.514 --> 00:33:13.930
What we are going
to care about is

00:33:13.930 --> 00:33:17.227
if you have some amazing
data about voting

00:33:17.227 --> 00:33:19.060
patterns in a particular
part of the country

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:24.500
that illuminate how a
certain demographic voted--

00:33:24.500 --> 00:33:26.150
that could be
really interesting.

00:33:28.660 --> 00:33:35.310
We had a pollster from Cornell
who did that and his material

00:33:35.310 --> 00:33:37.720
made it, it was only online
because we had such a flood

00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:39.430
of post-election stuff.

00:33:39.430 --> 00:33:42.100
But it just cut an interesting
slice out of the electorate

00:33:42.100 --> 00:33:43.720
that was really
interesting to us

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:47.620
and we thought illuminated
a part of what was going on.

00:33:47.620 --> 00:33:51.010
Presumably, any
researcher doing,

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:56.530
no matter how niche or esoteric,
has some sort of resonance

00:33:56.530 --> 00:34:00.610
for people and that's the
crucial part of figuring out

00:34:00.610 --> 00:34:05.230
whether you can make a New York
Times Op-Ed because we're not--

00:34:05.230 --> 00:34:09.100
as popular as we are in college
towns, most of our readers

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:10.690
are not academics,
most of our readers

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:12.606
are not going to know
your subjects very well.

00:34:12.606 --> 00:34:15.940
They're smart generalists,
they're sophisticated readers.

00:34:15.940 --> 00:34:19.150
What they want to do is to take
your nugget of information,

00:34:19.150 --> 00:34:23.889
your research whether it's
history or science or politics,

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:26.679
and your ability to
pull back and say

00:34:26.679 --> 00:34:29.796
this is why this matters to
lots of people is what's going

00:34:29.796 --> 00:34:31.420
can make the difference
between a piece

00:34:31.420 --> 00:34:32.739
that we take or don't take.

00:34:35.500 --> 00:34:39.320
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: How
many unassigned pieces

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:41.670
do you get over the
transom every day, roughly,

00:34:41.670 --> 00:34:43.400
an estimate?

00:34:43.400 --> 00:34:44.750
JAMES DAO: It's hundreds.

00:34:44.750 --> 00:34:49.694
And I personally will wake up to
30 in my inbox and many of them

00:34:49.694 --> 00:34:51.860
I will just farm out to
others to read, some of them

00:34:51.860 --> 00:34:54.052
I'll try to read.

00:34:54.052 --> 00:34:55.760
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
And what's the best--

00:34:55.760 --> 00:35:00.500
JAMES DAO: It's both a
blessing and a curse.

00:35:00.500 --> 00:35:02.160
It's not a curse--

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:04.910
the curse part of it isn't
just that it's a lot to read

00:35:04.910 --> 00:35:07.940
and we can't keep up with
it, but to some degree,

00:35:07.940 --> 00:35:12.530
we want to be able to direct
where the Op-Ed page is

00:35:12.530 --> 00:35:13.580
going on our own.

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:16.780
And we could just run
things that were sent to us

00:35:16.780 --> 00:35:21.500
every day of the week
for our entire careers.

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:23.420
What we try to do
as much as possible

00:35:23.420 --> 00:35:25.970
is to step back and
say here's a thought

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:28.406
that we think people
aren't dealing with

00:35:28.406 --> 00:35:30.530
and then think of who the
right writer is for that,

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:33.920
whether it's a novelist or
a journalist or an academic,

00:35:33.920 --> 00:35:37.580
and that's where your
relationships with editors

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:38.240
do matter.

00:35:38.240 --> 00:35:42.530
It not only helps you
when you do pitch a story,

00:35:42.530 --> 00:35:44.319
but sometimes we'll
come to you because we

00:35:44.319 --> 00:35:46.610
know that you've done research
on something interesting

00:35:46.610 --> 00:35:48.109
or we know that
you've just come out

00:35:48.109 --> 00:35:52.430
with a book on a particular
topic that was totally

00:35:52.430 --> 00:35:54.530
meaningless and obscure
to us until that moment

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:57.110
when, suddenly, it wasn't
and it really mattered.

00:35:57.110 --> 00:36:02.870
So our ability to have you on
our Rolodexes is important.

00:36:02.870 --> 00:36:04.260
But we publish--

00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:07.400
I don't know, we counted
it up the other day--

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:09.350
the operation I oversee
probably publishes

00:36:09.350 --> 00:36:14.930
over 100 things a week between
small online and long form

00:36:14.930 --> 00:36:16.550
in the Sunday Review.

00:36:16.550 --> 00:36:18.890
And then there's video
and now there's audio

00:36:18.890 --> 00:36:21.500
and there's just an incredible
array of things we now do.

00:36:26.180 --> 00:36:29.390
Weeding through that stuff
is a huge part of the day.

00:36:29.390 --> 00:36:35.990
And I guess, the last point to
go beyond the timeliness part

00:36:35.990 --> 00:36:39.440
of it is because Op-Ed has
evolved a lot in the years

00:36:39.440 --> 00:36:43.460
and it's not just policy,
problem, prescription type

00:36:43.460 --> 00:36:46.760
writing which is what it once
was and which we still value

00:36:46.760 --> 00:36:49.490
and we still do, particularly
at this moment when we have

00:36:49.490 --> 00:36:52.490
a new administration where
God knows where they're going,

00:36:52.490 --> 00:36:55.470
but you know, perhaps,
it's a persuadable moment

00:36:55.470 --> 00:36:58.880
and it's a time for
people to weigh in.

00:36:58.880 --> 00:37:05.382
But we also we also run first
person essays that are not even

00:37:05.382 --> 00:37:06.590
about a problem, necessarily.

00:37:06.590 --> 00:37:10.310
They're experiential, they're
beautifully written very often,

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:13.200
but they tell us something
about a place in the world

00:37:13.200 --> 00:37:17.270
or about a state of mind or
could be about a problem,

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:18.830
as well.

00:37:18.830 --> 00:37:23.942
And you know that
type of essay often

00:37:23.942 --> 00:37:25.400
is written by an
academic, as well.

00:37:28.550 --> 00:37:31.930
It's going to sound idiotic
for me to say this, but study

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:35.780
us, study not just
the daily Op-Ed page,

00:37:35.780 --> 00:37:38.990
but study the Sunday Review
and think about what you like

00:37:38.990 --> 00:37:40.730
and what works
for you and that's

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:44.150
a very important part of the
learning process in terms

00:37:44.150 --> 00:37:47.300
of figuring out what we
do and how your work might

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:49.700
fit into what we do.

00:37:49.700 --> 00:37:54.320
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Iris, so
you work in a different medium.

00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:56.660
On the one hand, you
do publish things

00:37:56.660 --> 00:38:00.110
that would look like
they could work in print

00:38:00.110 --> 00:38:04.020
or they could work on
cognoscente or [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:08.225
online and its portfolio.

00:38:08.225 --> 00:38:12.050
But I wanted you to talk about
the difference between what

00:38:12.050 --> 00:38:14.060
you're looking
for and who you're

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:18.340
looking for when you're
looking for Op-Ed pieces

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:19.760
we're going to hear.

00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:23.240
There's been an explosion
in the last couple of years

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:30.410
in listening to opinion and
this very energetic podcast

00:38:30.410 --> 00:38:35.000
environment that we're
enjoying right now.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:39.170
Talk a little bit about how
you're choosing or assigning

00:38:39.170 --> 00:38:43.530
that's different from what
your newspaper colleagues might

00:38:43.530 --> 00:38:44.030
be doing.

00:38:44.030 --> 00:38:45.405
IRIS ADLER: Well,
first of all, I

00:38:45.405 --> 00:38:47.780
would say that the
criteria we use to choose

00:38:47.780 --> 00:38:50.300
a good cognoscente piece--

00:38:50.300 --> 00:38:52.370
they're very similar
to the criteria

00:38:52.370 --> 00:38:55.430
we use for an on-air piece.

00:38:55.430 --> 00:38:58.880
And some of those attributes
have been talked about--

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:00.080
the ability to be concise.

00:39:03.020 --> 00:39:07.490
While our cognoscente pieces
might be up to 800 words,

00:39:07.490 --> 00:39:09.680
often we'll take
those exact pieces

00:39:09.680 --> 00:39:12.290
and turn them into
radio commentaries

00:39:12.290 --> 00:39:15.770
and then we face
said academia writer,

00:39:15.770 --> 00:39:20.930
we say, OK, now it's going to be
cut to 200 words or 300 words.

00:39:20.930 --> 00:39:26.390
It's really a shocking process
and we get a lot of resistance.

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:30.110
But as you all know,
it is very difficult

00:39:30.110 --> 00:39:34.130
to be listening to the radio
or whatever platform you listen

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:36.340
and have someone
just talk at you

00:39:36.340 --> 00:39:39.270
without the inclusion
of soundbytes

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:41.160
or other kinds of sounds.

00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:46.350
So the length,
literally, is two minutes

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:49.890
and that's what you get and
it's very difficult taking

00:39:49.890 --> 00:39:53.610
that writer from 800
words to two minutes,

00:39:53.610 --> 00:39:56.770
but it's absolutely critical and
some people don't want to do it

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:57.870
and that's fine.

00:39:57.870 --> 00:40:00.870
But in either case,
we really need

00:40:00.870 --> 00:40:03.470
to be very focused whether it's
a cognoscente piece or radio

00:40:03.470 --> 00:40:03.970
piece--

00:40:03.970 --> 00:40:05.970
I think someone has
talked-- but we're not

00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:08.370
dealing with big topics here.

00:40:08.370 --> 00:40:10.710
There was a very
prominent Harvard academic

00:40:10.710 --> 00:40:13.170
who used to write
for us and his topics

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:16.710
would be like how
do we fix education.

00:40:16.710 --> 00:40:21.210
I mean we really, really do need
a very small, but compelling

00:40:21.210 --> 00:40:23.230
byte.

00:40:23.230 --> 00:40:28.830
We also have emphasized
more particularly

00:40:28.830 --> 00:40:30.960
for the radio or
podcast, as you said,

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:33.030
this little narrative style.

00:40:33.030 --> 00:40:36.330
Ever since the huge success of
This American Life and serial

00:40:36.330 --> 00:40:39.120
that storytelling
narrative has sort of

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:43.050
infiltrated every part of the
audio world, whatever platform

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:44.320
we're talking about.

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:49.650
And so often in our cognoscente
pieces or our radio pieces,

00:40:49.650 --> 00:40:54.330
if the point could be wrapped
in some kind of narrative,

00:40:54.330 --> 00:40:57.090
it makes it more
compelling for the listener

00:40:57.090 --> 00:40:59.760
and people are just
used to this now.

00:40:59.760 --> 00:41:05.220
So we often help people try
and find something of a story

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:08.616
to help illustrate their point.

00:41:08.616 --> 00:41:11.910
One of the big differentiators--
and this sounds so obvious,

00:41:11.910 --> 00:41:14.700
but it's something we have
to explain to people all

00:41:14.700 --> 00:41:18.270
the time-- that just because
you're a brilliant writer

00:41:18.270 --> 00:41:23.880
does not mean that you're
a great voice on the radio.

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:25.800
And sometimes, you're
a brilliant talker

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:27.510
and then you get
someone in a studio,

00:41:27.510 --> 00:41:32.090
you put a mic in front of them,
and it's kind of daunting.

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:33.120
You've all done this.

00:41:33.120 --> 00:41:35.879
You're sitting there alone in
a studio, the mic, an engineer

00:41:35.879 --> 00:41:37.420
and producers sort
of talking at you.

00:41:37.420 --> 00:41:38.795
They're saying
now sound natural.

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:42.580
Not everybody could do it.

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:45.840
We have some people who do
it brilliantly all the time--

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:49.060
Nancy Gertner comes to mind
who we use a lot-- from the Law

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:49.560
School.

00:41:52.170 --> 00:41:54.450
So it's the actual
voice, but then there's

00:41:54.450 --> 00:41:57.090
what I call the
sort of voiciness.

00:41:57.090 --> 00:42:00.270
You could see why Naomi's a
great writer because she has--

00:42:00.270 --> 00:42:04.230
like right away, we would call
it like pops through the air.

00:42:04.230 --> 00:42:07.470
She just has that
kind of energy.

00:42:07.470 --> 00:42:12.300
And again, you can be brilliant
and articulate and just not

00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:15.219
be able to bring that
kind of energy that--

00:42:15.219 --> 00:42:17.010
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
Can someone learn that?

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:18.600
Can you help them achieve that?

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:20.550
IRIS ADLER: Here's what
I think you could do.

00:42:20.550 --> 00:42:22.200
You could have someone--

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:24.990
like literally, I tell people
stand in front of the mirror

00:42:24.990 --> 00:42:27.671
and practice every night and
record yourself and then listen

00:42:27.671 --> 00:42:28.170
back.

00:42:28.170 --> 00:42:30.480
Because when you
listen back, you really

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:33.360
get a sense of how flat
you could sound, how dull

00:42:33.360 --> 00:42:35.310
you could sound.

00:42:35.310 --> 00:42:39.420
And I will often coach people
as they're in the studio

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:41.820
and say it's going to sound
very exaggerated to you,

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:46.662
but you need to bring energy
and emphasis which goes back

00:42:46.662 --> 00:42:48.870
to the more important point
that if someone is really

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:51.660
passionate about a
topic, if they can bring

00:42:51.660 --> 00:42:55.560
that passion both to their
writing and to the air,

00:42:55.560 --> 00:43:02.700
it is really useful because
radio is a very intimate forum

00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:07.140
and it's very hard, I think,
to be inauthentic on the radio

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:11.920
or at least to be good.

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:14.510
You know people always
point to Ira Glass who's

00:43:14.510 --> 00:43:17.720
the-- you all know, the huge
radio This American Life star.

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:21.090
And he sounds when you
hear him on the air

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:26.430
so authentic just like he's
sitting down and just talking.

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:30.090
But every word that Ira
writes is written out

00:43:30.090 --> 00:43:31.800
and his ums are written.

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:34.230
This is the sort
of famous thing--

00:43:34.230 --> 00:43:37.154
you know those ums he
does and those like, wait,

00:43:37.154 --> 00:43:38.570
let me correct
myself here thing--

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:40.830
this is all written down.

00:43:40.830 --> 00:43:43.920
So people who are
really talented at it--

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:45.390
and they're few
and far between--

00:43:45.390 --> 00:43:47.670
know how to write
to sound authentic,

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:50.160
but for the rest of us, we
just need to be able to do it.

00:43:50.160 --> 00:43:53.220
And I think often, some
people, it's just practice

00:43:53.220 --> 00:43:56.100
and just getting
comfortable so they

00:43:56.100 --> 00:43:59.580
can sort of be self-revealing.

00:43:59.580 --> 00:44:02.456
For other people, they're
just not going to get there.

00:44:02.456 --> 00:44:04.830
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: You totally
ruined This American Life

00:44:04.830 --> 00:44:07.584
for many people today.

00:44:07.584 --> 00:44:09.750
NAOMI ORESKES: Now, you're
going to tell us Garrison

00:44:09.750 --> 00:44:10.749
Keillor isn't authentic.

00:44:10.749 --> 00:44:11.388
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:11.388 --> 00:44:12.792
IRIS ADLER: I don't know him.

00:44:12.792 --> 00:44:14.970
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
I wanted to ask just

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:16.410
so we know how the [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:18.970
I wanted to ask you guys one
more sort of lightning round

00:44:18.970 --> 00:44:23.460
question and we're going to
open it up to your questions

00:44:23.460 --> 00:44:27.000
and I want to assure you
all that I'm going to end

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:28.860
no later than a quarter to two.

00:44:28.860 --> 00:44:31.890
I know some of you have classes
to teach a, but b, some of you

00:44:31.890 --> 00:44:35.850
probably want to have some
