00:44:35.850 --> 00:44:38.570
with our guests here today, too.

00:44:38.570 --> 00:44:41.210
So they'll be there'll
be time for that.

00:44:41.210 --> 00:44:44.330
But the one sort of lightning
round question I wanted to ask

00:44:44.330 --> 00:44:50.240
is and, Jim, you hinted at it.

00:44:50.240 --> 00:44:55.820
So we've been talking about kind
of a traditional Op-Ed writing

00:44:55.820 --> 00:45:00.320
both for newspapers
and for radio,

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:05.810
but I wanted to talk about
innovations in this space.

00:45:05.810 --> 00:45:10.970
So The Times is
doing Op-Docs and we

00:45:10.970 --> 00:45:17.210
think now about aspects of
journalism being performative,

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:22.700
in a sense, and not to take away
from fairness or verisimilitude

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:26.840
or any of those
important traditions,

00:45:26.840 --> 00:45:32.570
but that just ink on paper
or pixels or airwaves--

00:45:32.570 --> 00:45:34.830
that it's not always sufficient.

00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:39.450
We're thinking about the
visual nature of these pieces.

00:45:39.450 --> 00:45:42.170
We are thinking about sound.

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:45.330
So if we could just
sort of quickly--

00:45:45.330 --> 00:45:48.950
and, Jim, I know The
Times has experimented

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:51.020
in this space a lot--
started some things,

00:45:51.020 --> 00:45:52.610
stopped some things.

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:55.010
But just if you could
each just really quickly

00:45:55.010 --> 00:45:57.380
talk about something that
you're excited about that's

00:45:57.380 --> 00:45:59.570
on the horizon
and how, maybe, we

00:45:59.570 --> 00:46:01.970
should be thinking differently
or more innovatively

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:04.931
about telling these stories.

00:46:04.931 --> 00:46:06.214
I'll start with you.

00:46:06.214 --> 00:46:07.380
JAMES DAO: Want me to start?

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:09.930
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Yeah.

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:12.730
JAMES DAO: Well, can
I name three things?

00:46:12.730 --> 00:46:21.090
So well, you mentioned or I
actually talked a little bit

00:46:21.090 --> 00:46:21.930
about The Stone.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:24.600
So one of the things we're
doing this coming year

00:46:24.600 --> 00:46:27.180
are mostly online.

00:46:27.180 --> 00:46:30.810
They're not blogs, but
they're formats, platforms

00:46:30.810 --> 00:46:33.110
for essentially essays.

00:46:33.110 --> 00:46:37.020
And I guess I can
talk about this.

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:39.660
It's a little bit
proprietary, but we're

00:46:39.660 --> 00:46:42.000
hoping to start one
on religion and just

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:45.690
talking about
religion in daily life

00:46:45.690 --> 00:46:49.650
from all religious points of
view, anywhere on the globe.

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:57.030
And we're expecting some of the
writers will be theologists,

00:46:57.030 --> 00:46:59.670
some of them will be
practicing ministers or rabbis,

00:46:59.670 --> 00:47:02.130
but we're hoping much of it
will be just people talking

00:47:02.130 --> 00:47:04.810
about religion and how it
guides their daily life

00:47:04.810 --> 00:47:06.750
through their
religious experiences

00:47:06.750 --> 00:47:09.150
from that sort of ground up.

00:47:09.150 --> 00:47:12.526
And that will, we're
hoping, have written essays,

00:47:12.526 --> 00:47:14.400
sometimes it will be
pieces off the news, who

00:47:14.400 --> 00:47:19.260
knows, if there's significant
news in the religion world.

00:47:19.260 --> 00:47:21.600
Some of it we're hoping
will be audio, some of it

00:47:21.600 --> 00:47:22.860
could be video, as well.

00:47:22.860 --> 00:47:25.530
And that will be
just its own thing

00:47:25.530 --> 00:47:28.540
we're hoping to create
in the coming year.

00:47:28.540 --> 00:47:34.500
Similarly, we're planning
a mainly online feature

00:47:34.500 --> 00:47:41.790
on Vietnam and how Vietnam
the war that has shaped

00:47:41.790 --> 00:47:45.210
American life today in all
its many ways, whether it's

00:47:45.210 --> 00:47:51.720
having to do with foreign
policy or military policy,

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:55.380
military strategy, how
Vietnam was experienced

00:47:55.380 --> 00:47:57.330
and still how the war
is still experienced

00:47:57.330 --> 00:47:59.370
by people in Vietnam today.

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:01.260
And that's going to
be a running feature

00:48:01.260 --> 00:48:02.460
over the course of the year.

00:48:02.460 --> 00:48:04.543
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Will
you bring in other media?

00:48:04.543 --> 00:48:05.070
Not just--

00:48:05.070 --> 00:48:05.980
JAMES DAO: Yep.

00:48:05.980 --> 00:48:07.652
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: OK.

00:48:07.652 --> 00:48:09.610
JAMES DAO: We're doing
this sort of in conjunct

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:13.530
with Ken Burns who's got a big
series coming out on Vietnam.

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:20.820
We are playing with, as I
was talking to Iris and Katie

00:48:20.820 --> 00:48:28.060
about, with audio and trying to
go the route of doing podcasts.

00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:29.757
And those are still
being worked on.

00:48:29.757 --> 00:48:31.590
We haven't quite figured
out how to do them,

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:33.690
but certainly some
of it will probably

00:48:33.690 --> 00:48:37.920
involve some of our columnists,
people like maybe Gail Collins

00:48:37.920 --> 00:48:41.910
or Nick Krostof's kind of a
natural for any experiment

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:47.040
that you want to try whether
it's social media or video.

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:49.560
And now we're going to launch
him on audio maybe and see

00:48:49.560 --> 00:48:50.185
how that works.

00:48:50.185 --> 00:48:53.304
360 video is the other
thing he's going to try.

00:48:53.304 --> 00:48:54.220
It's an amazing thing.

00:48:54.220 --> 00:48:56.345
The camera's-- I don't know
if anybody's seen them,

00:48:56.345 --> 00:49:00.960
but 360 video cameras are the
size of a tennis ball and you

00:49:00.960 --> 00:49:04.080
can put them down and just
let them run for a couple

00:49:04.080 --> 00:49:06.660
of minutes and it's just
going to be a whole other part

00:49:06.660 --> 00:49:08.910
of what we do, both in the
newsroom and in the opinion

00:49:08.910 --> 00:49:09.502
section.

00:49:09.502 --> 00:49:10.460
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: OK.

00:49:10.460 --> 00:49:12.990
Katie, I have an example
in my head for The Globe,

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:15.060
but maybe you want to
talk about a different one

00:49:15.060 --> 00:49:20.010
and that was the approach you
took to writing about guns--

00:49:20.010 --> 00:49:21.240
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Oh, sure.

00:49:21.240 --> 00:49:24.570
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: --which
included a massive tweet

00:49:24.570 --> 00:49:25.479
storm--

00:49:25.479 --> 00:49:26.520
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Yeah.

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:28.590
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: --along
with the print presentation,

00:49:28.590 --> 00:49:31.048
but maybe you could just talk
a little bit about that which

00:49:31.048 --> 00:49:34.360
I thought was very innovative in
that space and with that issue.

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:36.026
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY:
And that's something

00:49:36.026 --> 00:49:38.550
that we've actually been
experimenting, generally, with.

00:49:38.550 --> 00:49:41.220
I would echo, we're also
doing a lot of experimenting

00:49:41.220 --> 00:49:42.330
with 360 video.

00:49:42.330 --> 00:49:45.150
We're currently working
with some MIT academics

00:49:45.150 --> 00:49:48.060
on a project mapping
the Charles River.

00:49:48.060 --> 00:49:50.884
We have access to
the USS Constitution

00:49:50.884 --> 00:49:52.800
that's in dry-docks right
now that we're doing

00:49:52.800 --> 00:49:55.690
this cool history project on.

00:49:55.690 --> 00:49:57.690
And what Ann Marie
is referring to

00:49:57.690 --> 00:50:01.410
is a editorial that
we wrote back in June.

00:50:01.410 --> 00:50:05.640
It was a project
that I led looking

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:08.100
in the aftermath of
the Orlando shooting,

00:50:08.100 --> 00:50:13.440
calling for a ban
on assault rifles.

00:50:13.440 --> 00:50:15.330
And what we did for
that project is we

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:17.770
approached it in three ways--

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:20.940
one for print, one for
our online desktop,

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:24.570
mobile experience,
and then for social.

00:50:24.570 --> 00:50:28.260
The print product was probably
something that all of you

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:30.550
would be very familiar with.

00:50:30.550 --> 00:50:33.000
We wrapped the front
page of The Globe

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:36.960
on a Thursday morning
with the editorial

00:50:36.960 --> 00:50:41.910
as well as some graphics kind
of making the case that we

00:50:41.910 --> 00:50:43.590
should ban assault rifles.

00:50:43.590 --> 00:50:48.900
Then, we wrote a very
traditional editorial.

00:50:48.900 --> 00:50:52.500
And then for digital,
it was much more

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:54.120
of an interactive experience.

00:50:54.120 --> 00:50:56.610
We also had several
calls to action within it

00:50:56.610 --> 00:50:59.160
so we targeted six
senators that we

00:50:59.160 --> 00:51:01.350
knew were vulnerable
on this topic

00:51:01.350 --> 00:51:04.200
and asked them to change
their vote and most of them

00:51:04.200 --> 00:51:07.590
lost at the beginning
of November.

00:51:07.590 --> 00:51:12.050
They received thousands of
tweets via The Boston Globe

00:51:12.050 --> 00:51:16.920
website and that was something
that was really heartening.

00:51:16.920 --> 00:51:18.750
Kelly Ayotte was
one, in particular,

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:22.650
that probably because
of the local ties that

00:51:22.650 --> 00:51:26.880
came under assault, basically,
off from The Globe's website

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:29.790
and ultimately changed her vote
which was something that we

00:51:29.790 --> 00:51:32.100
were really proud to see.

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:35.940
And then finally, we did this
really innovative project which

00:51:35.940 --> 00:51:39.570
is something we're
experimenting with more and more

00:51:39.570 --> 00:51:42.450
of on social.

00:51:42.450 --> 00:51:45.900
Every five seconds or excuse
me, every five minutes,

00:51:45.900 --> 00:51:55.200
we posted the name and age
of a gun mass shooting victim

00:51:55.200 --> 00:51:59.537
since Sandy Hook and
the killings there.

00:51:59.537 --> 00:52:00.120
And that was--

00:52:00.120 --> 00:52:01.582
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Every
single American victim

00:52:01.582 --> 00:52:02.010
since Sandy Hook.

00:52:02.010 --> 00:52:03.176
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Exactly.

00:52:03.176 --> 00:52:06.390
Well, every single victim of a
shooting in the United States.

00:52:06.390 --> 00:52:07.230
Some of them were--

00:52:07.230 --> 00:52:09.010
a couple of them were
actually foreigners.

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:15.150
But the power of
that was something

00:52:15.150 --> 00:52:17.850
we were experimenting with
and we weren't expecting,

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:20.580
but the power of that
to see those names

00:52:20.580 --> 00:52:23.940
and to see how frequently they
came and this was something

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:26.760
that took 38 hours
for us to accomplish

00:52:26.760 --> 00:52:28.740
was to list every victim's name.

00:52:28.740 --> 00:52:31.080
We had a very stringent
standard for who

00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:37.950
would be included in that list,
and yet, it took that long.

00:52:37.950 --> 00:52:44.280
We took over The Globe's
Twitter handle and particularly

00:52:44.280 --> 00:52:48.210
the part when we are talking
about the children who

00:52:48.210 --> 00:52:52.920
have died that it became very
poignant very quickly to see

00:52:52.920 --> 00:52:56.820
those names come
one after the other

00:52:56.820 --> 00:53:00.600
and ending on the Orlando
Pulse Nightclub shooting.

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:02.790
Just to kind of see
the raw power of that

00:53:02.790 --> 00:53:05.940
was something that we've
tried to take and apply

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:07.120
in other ways.

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:10.020
So we're actually now,
almost in every major project

00:53:10.020 --> 00:53:13.650
that we do through the
newsroom and the Op-Ed page,

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:15.960
looking at it through that
lens of what should we

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:20.730
be doing in print, what
should we be doing in digital,

00:53:20.730 --> 00:53:22.320
and what should we
be doing on social.

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:26.370
And we just had a huge
piece about trolley accident

00:53:26.370 --> 00:53:30.970
that happened 100 years ago that
