00:53:30.970 --> 00:53:33.170
and had a lot of success with.

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:35.070
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
So, Naomi, I'm

00:53:35.070 --> 00:53:37.710
wondering if you think
about your pieces now.

00:53:37.710 --> 00:53:41.280
You talked about how when
you wrote that first piece

00:53:41.280 --> 00:53:46.170
for the LA Times these
options didn't really exist.

00:53:46.170 --> 00:53:48.390
Do you think about
that more acutely now?

00:53:48.390 --> 00:53:50.700
It's not just I write this
thing, I give it to them,

00:53:50.700 --> 00:53:52.010
it goes into the newspaper.

00:53:52.010 --> 00:53:54.330
Are you thinking about
building audience

00:53:54.330 --> 00:53:57.631
or trying new forms
of storytelling?

00:53:57.631 --> 00:53:58.380
NAOMI ORESKES: OK.

00:53:58.380 --> 00:54:00.088
To me, those are two
different questions.

00:54:00.088 --> 00:54:02.130
In terms of the
format, not so much.

00:54:02.130 --> 00:54:06.060
I mean different
things come your way.

00:54:06.060 --> 00:54:07.050
I love radio.

00:54:07.050 --> 00:54:09.810
I have to say radio is my
