always say yes the opportunity

00:54:20.580 --> 00:54:21.371
to be on the radio.

00:54:21.371 --> 00:54:23.730
So don't be afraid of radio.

00:54:23.730 --> 00:54:26.490
Radio is an academic's dream
come true because it's you

00:54:26.490 --> 00:54:28.860
and your words and
your voice so I just

00:54:28.860 --> 00:54:31.290
think radio is fantastic.

00:54:31.290 --> 00:54:33.180
I wouldn't say that
it's changed how

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:35.820
I think about what I'm doing.

00:54:35.820 --> 00:54:37.320
I'm not sitting
around thinking, oh,

00:54:37.320 --> 00:54:38.630
could I do a podcast on this?

00:54:38.630 --> 00:54:41.400
I'm not doing that,
although maybe I will--

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:43.140
I don't know.

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:44.782
But in terms of the
storytelling part,

00:54:44.782 --> 00:54:46.240
absolutely definitely
and actually,

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:48.090
my great postdoc,
Jeff Zupan, is here

00:54:48.090 --> 00:54:51.510
who's working with me right
now on a kind of novel approach

00:54:51.510 --> 00:54:53.550
to climate change solutions.

00:54:53.550 --> 00:54:56.850
So yes, I've certainly been
thinking about that for a while

00:54:56.850 --> 00:54:59.575
and I would say my
work with journalists

00:54:59.575 --> 00:55:01.950
and the work I've done trying
to reach a broader audience

00:55:01.950 --> 00:55:03.990
has certainly made
me think much more

00:55:03.990 --> 00:55:08.640
about how we tell
our stories and why,

00:55:08.640 --> 00:55:12.480
as academics, what some of
the obstacles are for us.

00:55:12.480 --> 00:55:15.420
That as academics, we
have certain conventions

00:55:15.420 --> 00:55:18.390
of academic life that
we subscribe to that

00:55:18.390 --> 00:55:20.640
absolutely do get in the way--

00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:22.300
no question about that.

00:55:22.300 --> 00:55:24.330
And so I think where
I'm at right now

00:55:24.330 --> 00:55:26.610
and I hope Judy's
listening very closely,

00:55:26.610 --> 00:55:28.320
I'm not so much
interested in changing

00:55:28.320 --> 00:55:31.680
what I do for journalists.

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:33.180
I'm pretty happy
with what I've done

00:55:33.180 --> 00:55:35.340
in the journalistic
popular domain.

00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:38.510
It's more like I think I'd
like to become involved now

00:55:38.510 --> 00:55:41.700
in a movement to change how
academics write for each other

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:45.390
because I've come to think I
don't actually understand why

00:55:45.390 --> 00:55:48.930
we, as academics, insist
on writing books that

00:55:48.930 --> 00:55:52.080
are excruciatingly boring
and that no one will read.

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:54.870
I mean it makes no sense
to me and I'm fully

00:55:54.870 --> 00:55:56.362
tenured so I can say this now--

00:55:56.362 --> 00:55:57.820
and I'm not looking
for another job

00:55:57.820 --> 00:56:00.360
and I don't want to be a dean.

00:56:00.360 --> 00:56:02.070
But really, I mean
it's really this kind

00:56:02.070 --> 00:56:05.520
of extremely interesting mystery
about how and why we write

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:07.170
these incredibly
boring books that only

00:56:07.170 --> 00:56:08.794
17 other people in
our field would read

00:56:08.794 --> 00:56:10.530
and it wasn't always that way.

00:56:10.530 --> 00:56:12.742
And as a historian of
science, I can tell you

00:56:12.742 --> 00:56:14.700
that we had Harvard
professors of geology right

00:56:14.700 --> 00:56:16.920
here in this institution
who, in the 1920s,

00:56:16.920 --> 00:56:20.880
were writing bestsellers
about continental drift, what

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:23.250
would have been considered
a very academic topic.

00:56:23.250 --> 00:56:27.180
So some of the issues about
why we, as academics, do

00:56:27.180 --> 00:56:28.770
the things we do,
so I'd like to see

00:56:28.770 --> 00:56:32.580
the academic side of this
world begin to move and shift

00:56:32.580 --> 00:56:36.300
and think more about who our
audience is and why have we

00:56:36.300 --> 00:56:39.075
defined our audience in such
an excruciating now way.

00:56:39.075 --> 00:56:40.450
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
That's great.

