New York Times, Washington Post,

01:05:27.540 --> 01:05:29.570
The Boston Globe,
you know wherever,

01:05:29.570 --> 01:05:32.987
you would see those quotations
juxtaposed with a scientist,

01:05:32.987 --> 01:05:34.820
therefore creating the
impression that there

01:05:34.820 --> 01:05:37.153
was a scientific debate which,
as I've shown in my work,

01:05:37.153 --> 01:05:40.010
is the whole point of
that kind of thing.

01:05:40.010 --> 01:05:42.770
So that's one
question I have is I

01:05:42.770 --> 01:05:46.460
guess my perception from my
view is that the media, the news

01:05:46.460 --> 01:05:49.490
media, have not been as
alert to that problem

01:05:49.490 --> 01:05:51.704
as I think they need to
be-- that's one thing.

01:05:51.704 --> 01:05:53.870
And even though many
journalists I've talked to say,

01:05:53.870 --> 01:05:55.078
oh, we don't do that anymore.

01:05:55.078 --> 01:05:56.810
We don't make that
mistake anymore.

01:05:56.810 --> 01:06:00.500
We know we shouldn't do that,
yet I see it all the time.

01:06:00.500 --> 01:06:03.620
And then the other part has
to do with the Opinion page

01:06:03.620 --> 01:06:05.480
and this is a tricky
one because, obviously,

01:06:05.480 --> 01:06:06.930
opinion pages are opinions.

01:06:06.930 --> 01:06:10.040
But I have seen cases-- and I'm
going to be specific to The New

01:06:10.040 --> 01:06:13.160
York Times now because
I'm using facts--

01:06:13.160 --> 01:06:15.650
where someone on
the opinion page,

01:06:15.650 --> 01:06:19.049
either a guest writer or
one of your own columnists--

01:06:19.049 --> 01:06:21.590
and if you're interested, later,
I can tell you offline who--

01:06:21.590 --> 01:06:24.440
has said something in an
opinion a matter of fact

01:06:24.440 --> 01:06:27.500
that was demonstrably false
and used a false claim

01:06:27.500 --> 01:06:29.177
to build the opinion piece.

01:06:29.177 --> 01:06:31.010
And one time-- this
happened a few years ago

01:06:31.010 --> 01:06:33.830
before I had friends on the
editorial page who I would now

01:06:33.830 --> 01:06:36.136
reach out to and call--
but where this happened

01:06:36.136 --> 01:06:37.760
with a particular
columnist where I had

01:06:37.760 --> 01:06:39.260
seen it happen more than once.

01:06:39.260 --> 01:06:42.080
And on the third time, it
happened to be about a topic

01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:44.270
that I knew very well that
one of my own students

01:06:44.270 --> 01:06:47.060
had written their honors
thesis on was a claim that

01:06:47.060 --> 01:06:48.340
was demonstrably false--

01:06:48.340 --> 01:06:50.000
I had the documentation.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:53.030
And I did send something
to The New York Times,

01:06:53.030 --> 01:06:54.145
never received any reply.

01:06:56.810 --> 01:06:58.300
Yeah.

01:06:58.300 --> 01:07:03.720
And that false claim is now,
if you go to The New York Times

01:07:03.720 --> 01:07:05.330
microfiche, it's there.

01:07:05.330 --> 01:07:07.070
So I guess I have two questions.

01:07:07.070 --> 01:07:10.460
One is about how you think
about it, but the more important

01:07:10.460 --> 01:07:13.251
question, I think, for this
audience is, what should we do?

01:07:13.251 --> 01:07:14.750
So we're reading
The New York Times,

01:07:14.750 --> 01:07:17.870
we see something that we know is
false as scholars and academics

01:07:17.870 --> 01:07:20.510
who have worked on
it, yet it's now there

01:07:20.510 --> 01:07:22.760
in The New York Times.

01:07:22.760 --> 01:07:24.800
What is the right
way for us to try

01:07:24.800 --> 01:07:27.860
to engage with you to try to
correct something like that

01:07:27.860 --> 01:07:29.715
and prevent that
from happening again?

01:07:29.715 --> 01:07:31.050
JAMES DAO: Sure.

01:07:31.050 --> 01:07:33.410
So we pride ourselves
in how many corrections

01:07:33.410 --> 01:07:35.050
we run and we run a lot.

01:07:35.050 --> 01:07:38.930
And they can be
unbelievably arcane,

01:07:38.930 --> 01:07:41.990
but it's a crucial
part of what we do.

01:07:41.990 --> 01:07:48.440
And as both the newsroom
employee and a newsroom editor

01:07:48.440 --> 01:07:51.260
and now the Op-Ed
editor, I generally

01:07:51.260 --> 01:07:54.950
believe that we should err on
the side of correcting when

01:07:54.950 --> 01:07:58.120
we can, because sometimes
it is a little bit

01:07:58.120 --> 01:07:59.870
hard to get to get to
ground truth on some

01:07:59.870 --> 01:08:01.560
of the issues that come up.

01:08:01.560 --> 01:08:06.460
But the columnists, believe
it or not, make mistakes.

01:08:06.460 --> 01:08:08.690
In fact, I woke up this
morning to two complaints

01:08:08.690 --> 01:08:12.350
about columns over the weekend
and we will take that up

01:08:12.350 --> 01:08:12.854
with them.

01:08:12.854 --> 01:08:14.270
They have their
own fact checkers.

01:08:14.270 --> 01:08:19.040
They try to run this stuff
through their own process,

01:08:19.040 --> 01:08:23.149
but journalism is an
incredibly imperfect process

01:08:23.149 --> 01:08:25.970
and that goes for
the Op-Ed page, too.

01:08:25.970 --> 01:08:30.020
We are a self-correcting
institution

01:08:30.020 --> 01:08:34.189
and we self-correct in two ways.

01:08:34.189 --> 01:08:36.350
Sometimes, when there's
a clear factual error

01:08:36.350 --> 01:08:39.620
that somebody can tell us
is a clear factual error,

01:08:39.620 --> 01:08:40.880
we will push--

01:08:40.880 --> 01:08:43.939
most editors attitude is we
will do a correction on it

01:08:43.939 --> 01:08:45.920
and that will go
online under the piece

01:08:45.920 --> 01:08:48.680
as well as in the paper.

01:08:48.680 --> 01:08:52.340
Sometimes, the
problems of coverage

01:08:52.340 --> 01:08:56.529
are more nuanced or complicated
and they're not simple facts.

01:08:56.529 --> 01:08:58.520
And we correct by
trying to come up

01:08:58.520 --> 01:09:00.979
with different viewpoints or
different types of stories

01:09:00.979 --> 01:09:03.140
to broaden the
understanding of an issue

01:09:03.140 --> 01:09:07.102
beyond what might have been a
less than accurate portrayal.

01:09:07.102 --> 01:09:09.560
NAOMI ORESKES: But if I can
just press slightly, I'm sorry,

01:09:09.560 --> 01:09:10.490
but what should we do?

01:09:10.490 --> 01:09:12.698
Because when I did reach
out, I never got a response.

01:09:12.698 --> 01:09:14.979
And how do we communicate
with you about these issues?

01:09:14.979 --> 01:09:16.062
JAMES DAO: There is this--

01:09:16.062 --> 01:09:18.620
I'll be honest, I don't
know where you find it,

01:09:18.620 --> 01:09:21.680
but we have a corrections
editor for the entire news

01:09:21.680 --> 01:09:22.450
organization.

01:09:22.450 --> 01:09:24.200
NAOMI ORESKES: You
mean the public editor?

01:09:24.200 --> 01:09:25.844
JAMES DAO: No, you can go to
the public editor, if you want,

01:09:25.844 --> 01:09:27.920
and a public editor
may take it up

01:09:27.920 --> 01:09:31.370
or they may send the note to me.

01:09:31.370 --> 01:09:33.140
But there is an editor
who just handles

01:09:33.140 --> 01:09:33.859
corrections for the entire--

01:09:33.859 --> 01:09:34.310
NAOMI ORESKES: So
that's the right place

01:09:34.310 --> 01:09:35.435
to go, not the Op-Ed page.

01:09:35.435 --> 01:09:36.560
JAMES DAO: And I'm trying--

01:09:36.560 --> 01:09:40.910
I don't know the email off
hand, but it's probably

01:09:40.910 --> 01:09:44.910
where you find corrections
in the newspaper.

01:09:44.910 --> 01:09:47.561
You will see an email there
and you send your correction

01:09:47.561 --> 01:09:50.060
to there and, believe it or
not, they go through all of them

01:09:50.060 --> 01:09:53.210
and then they either
dispel them immediately

01:09:53.210 --> 01:09:55.370
if it doesn't look like
it's a correctable error

01:09:55.370 --> 01:09:57.050
or they send it off
to people like me

01:09:57.050 --> 01:09:59.756
and then I give it to
another editor who will then

01:09:59.756 --> 01:10:00.880
try to get to ground truth.

01:10:00.880 --> 01:10:03.720
So we are constantly
dealing-- and that's really--

01:10:03.720 --> 01:10:06.520
if you know an editor, you
can always send them a note.

01:10:06.520 --> 01:10:07.510
NAOMI ORESKES: And that's
what I would do now.

01:10:07.510 --> 01:10:09.343
Just curious, though,
because lots of people

01:10:09.343 --> 01:10:10.990
don't necessarily know editors.

01:10:10.990 --> 01:10:15.460
JAMES DAO: But there is a public
process and it's laid out,

01:10:15.460 --> 01:10:18.190
I think it's probably a whole
page on The Times website

01:10:18.190 --> 01:10:20.250
that explains the
corrections process.

01:10:20.250 --> 01:10:21.740
IRIS ADLER: Yeah.

01:10:21.740 --> 01:10:24.690
AUDIENCE: I am Brigitte
Madrian and I'm a professor

01:10:24.690 --> 01:10:25.940
at the Harvard Kennedy School.

01:10:25.940 --> 01:10:28.610
I work on the behavioral
economics of household

01:10:28.610 --> 01:10:30.440
financial decision making.

01:10:30.440 --> 01:10:33.290
I have, I guess, a more
logistical question.

01:10:33.290 --> 01:10:36.290
So in my discipline,
economics, if you're

01:10:36.290 --> 01:10:39.230
trying to publish
a paper, it would

01:10:39.230 --> 01:10:41.870
be considered an
ethical violation

01:10:41.870 --> 01:10:45.020
to submit your paper to
more than one journal

01:10:45.020 --> 01:10:46.334
at the same time.

01:10:46.334 --> 01:10:48.500
On the other hand, if you're
trying to write a book,

01:10:48.500 --> 01:10:50.540
you could shop your
book proposal around

01:10:50.540 --> 01:10:53.090
to multiple publishers
and find the best deal.

01:10:53.090 --> 01:10:55.610
So I guess I'm asking for those
of us who have never written

01:10:55.610 --> 01:10:59.210
an Op-Ed before, what are
the ethical norms for getting

01:10:59.210 --> 01:11:00.860
an Op-Ed published?

01:11:00.860 --> 01:11:03.230
Can you only shop it
around one place at a time

01:11:03.230 --> 01:11:05.000
so you have to do
it sequentially?

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:08.690
Or could you send it to
200 different outlets

01:11:08.690 --> 01:11:11.180
and if 150 of them
say they love it,

01:11:11.180 --> 01:11:13.160
you could publish it
in all 150 of them?

01:11:15.880 --> 01:11:18.650
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: I would
say definitely, one at a time.

01:11:18.650 --> 01:11:21.980
Never offer an Op-Ed
to an editor that's not

01:11:21.980 --> 01:11:23.485
an exclusive to that editor.

01:11:27.710 --> 01:11:31.040
JAMES DAO: Yeah, I
would second that.

01:11:31.040 --> 01:11:32.600
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
So can I just

01:11:32.600 --> 01:11:35.000
then ask about the
tension between

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:41.750
that sequential offering and
earlier comments about you're

01:11:41.750 --> 01:11:44.480
getting things within
an hour of an event

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:47.150
and you want things
that are very--

01:11:47.150 --> 01:11:49.850
three days from now is too late.

01:11:49.850 --> 01:11:52.640
So that system presumes
that an editor's

01:11:52.640 --> 01:11:55.460
getting back to you
instantly to say I love or I

01:11:55.460 --> 01:11:57.200
don't love this piece.

01:11:57.200 --> 01:11:59.270
So how do you navigate
between those?

01:11:59.270 --> 01:12:02.840
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: I often
suggest putting an expire time

01:12:02.840 --> 01:12:05.960
or date on your email
saying if I don't hear back

01:12:05.960 --> 01:12:08.720
from you by this time, then I
will assume that you are not

01:12:08.720 --> 01:12:12.070
interested and I will move on.

01:12:12.070 --> 01:12:16.370
I frequently find myself,
I can't speak for Jim,

01:12:16.370 --> 01:12:21.110
but I have 56,000 emails
that are unread right now.

01:12:21.110 --> 01:12:22.280
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:22.280 --> 01:12:24.710
NAOMI ORESKES: That
makes me feel better.

01:12:24.710 --> 01:12:26.720
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: I
literally get thousands

01:12:26.720 --> 01:12:32.420
of e-mails every day and it's
a combination of the fact

01:12:32.420 --> 01:12:37.610
that I have always had a foot
in the newsroom and a foot

01:12:37.610 --> 01:12:43.940
in opinion and with ideas, we
did reported pieces and opinion

01:12:43.940 --> 01:12:46.880
pieces so I think I get
more than most people.

01:12:46.880 --> 01:12:50.480
But the point
being, I often find

01:12:50.480 --> 01:12:55.250
myself sending a note to
someone whose pitch I am reading

01:12:55.250 --> 01:13:00.140
a day later or two days later
then I should be and saying,

01:13:00.140 --> 01:13:01.880
have you placed
this somewhere else?

01:13:01.880 --> 01:13:03.680
I don't have the
expectation that you've

01:13:03.680 --> 01:13:07.160
been waiting for me
to get back to you

01:13:07.160 --> 01:13:10.510
because of that timeliness and
that importance and timeliness.

01:13:10.510 --> 01:13:12.200
So as long as you're
clear up front

01:13:12.200 --> 01:13:15.710
saying, if I don't hear
from you by this time,

01:13:15.710 --> 01:13:18.144
I think that's fair game to
move on to the next place.

01:13:18.144 --> 01:13:19.310
JAMES DAO: It's good advice.

01:13:19.310 --> 01:13:20.450
NAOMI ORESKES: I can
make one suggestion

01:13:20.450 --> 01:13:21.800
that could be helpful, too.

01:13:21.800 --> 01:13:23.990
Sometimes, you might have
an idea for something,

01:13:23.990 --> 01:13:25.970
like something's
coming up and you

01:13:25.970 --> 01:13:28.860
anticipate that you might
have something to say.

01:13:28.860 --> 01:13:30.710
So one of the pieces
I'm most proud of

01:13:30.710 --> 01:13:32.450
was one I did in
The Washington Post

01:13:32.450 --> 01:13:35.840
when the fourth assessment
report of the IPCC came out.

01:13:35.840 --> 01:13:37.640
And I knew that wants
to report came out,

01:13:37.640 --> 01:13:39.350
they would be swamped
with suggestions,

01:13:39.350 --> 01:13:40.725
but I had an idea
for something I

01:13:40.725 --> 01:13:43.280
wanted to say in
advance of the release.

01:13:43.280 --> 01:13:45.410
And so I sent it to them
two weeks ahead of time.

01:13:45.410 --> 01:13:48.060
I said, here's a piece
that's anticipating

01:13:48.060 --> 01:13:49.310
the release of the AR4.

01:13:49.310 --> 01:13:52.040
I think this would be great
to run a couple of days

01:13:52.040 --> 01:13:53.570
before it comes out.

01:13:53.570 --> 01:13:56.840
And they did and that
piece got huge attention

01:13:56.840 --> 01:13:59.324
because it was actually
ahead of the curve.

01:13:59.324 --> 01:14:00.740
And if you do
something like that,

01:14:00.740 --> 01:14:02.156
then you have a
little bit of room

01:14:02.156 --> 01:14:04.592
to maneuver, too,
because as Kathleen said,

01:14:04.592 --> 01:14:06.550
often, editors don't get
back to you right away

01:14:06.550 --> 01:14:09.300
and then you are in this awkward
position of am I waiting or am

01:14:09.300 --> 01:14:09.957
I moving on?

01:14:09.957 --> 01:14:11.540
And usually, what I
do if that happens

01:14:11.540 --> 01:14:13.942
is I'll send a follow up
saying, if you're interested,

01:14:13.942 --> 01:14:15.650
please let me know,
if not, I'm moving on

01:14:15.650 --> 01:14:16.761
and then you can move on.

01:14:16.761 --> 01:14:18.760
But definitely, if you
can anticipate and get it

01:14:18.760 --> 01:14:22.310
in ahead of time, that gives you
both a bit of room to maneuver.

01:14:22.310 --> 01:14:24.830
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: That's
great, great, great advice.

01:14:24.830 --> 01:14:26.390
I mean, editors are
always assigning

01:14:26.390 --> 01:14:30.570
their reporters
anticipatorily-- is that a word?

01:14:30.570 --> 01:14:32.510
And so to think
about that for Op-Eds

01:14:32.510 --> 01:14:35.060
is a really good
piece of advice.

01:14:35.060 --> 01:14:36.284
You had your hand up.

01:14:36.284 --> 01:14:36.950
AUDIENCE: I did?

01:14:36.950 --> 01:14:37.560
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
Oh, you didn't.

01:14:37.560 --> 01:14:38.161
OK.

01:14:38.161 --> 01:14:39.410
AUDIENCE: Well, I sort of did.

01:14:39.410 --> 01:14:40.743
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Sort of did?

01:14:40.743 --> 01:14:42.452
AUDIENCE: It was a
follow up to this--

01:14:42.452 --> 01:14:43.380
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
Jeff, say who you are.

01:14:43.380 --> 01:14:43.850
AUDIENCE: Oh, hi.

01:14:43.850 --> 01:14:44.720
I'm Jeffrey Zupan.

01:14:44.720 --> 01:14:47.470
I'm Naomi's postdoc.

01:14:47.470 --> 01:14:49.090
It was a follow up
to that discussion

01:14:49.090 --> 01:14:51.110
where I've often
been in a situation

01:14:51.110 --> 01:14:53.360
where there's a
timeliness to an issue

01:14:53.360 --> 01:14:55.907
and you'd love for it to
have the impact of The Times

01:14:55.907 --> 01:14:57.240
or Globe or something like that.

01:14:57.240 --> 01:14:58.737
But you have a
Huffington Post blog

01:14:58.737 --> 01:15:00.320
and you could just
post it in an hour.

01:15:00.320 --> 01:15:03.884
And so there's that
deliberation as to how long--

01:15:03.884 --> 01:15:05.300
you say you're not
waiting for us,

01:15:05.300 --> 01:15:07.591
but we're waiting for you,
like we'd love to hear back.

01:15:07.591 --> 01:15:10.340
So is it appropriate
to literally

01:15:10.340 --> 01:15:13.680
give you just five hours
notice or something like that?

01:15:13.680 --> 01:15:17.510
I always felt rude putting
such a hard time stamp.

01:15:17.510 --> 01:15:20.450
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: I think it's
really a case by case basis.

01:15:20.450 --> 01:15:25.540
If it's something like you want
to respond to claims that there

01:15:25.540 --> 01:15:31.890
has been a genocide in x country
and that news has just broke,

01:15:31.890 --> 01:15:37.390
then I think giving
editors five hours is fine.

01:15:37.390 --> 01:15:41.250
I think if it's something
that is a week from now,

01:15:41.250 --> 01:15:45.120
we know this report is going
to be released, give me

01:15:45.120 --> 01:15:45.780
a day or two.

01:15:49.167 --> 01:15:51.000
And I also think the
other thing I would add

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:54.990
is it's always appropriate to
follow up because there are

01:15:54.990 --> 01:15:57.510
often times when I
miss the first email,

01:15:57.510 --> 01:15:59.410
but the second email
for some reason--

01:15:59.410 --> 01:16:01.500
it's quieter or there's
something happening

01:16:01.500 --> 01:16:05.530
and I can get to it faster.

01:16:05.530 --> 01:16:11.680
But I would say you're
selling something

01:16:11.680 --> 01:16:13.680
when you're trying to put
your opinion out there

01:16:13.680 --> 01:16:18.270
and you have every right
to say this offer expires,

01:16:18.270 --> 01:16:18.870
I would say.

01:16:21.279 --> 01:16:22.279
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Yes.

01:16:24.879 --> 01:16:25.420
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:16:25.420 --> 01:16:28.357
I'm Melani Cammett from
the Government department

01:16:28.357 --> 01:16:30.190
and I have a question
that's sort of related

01:16:30.190 --> 01:16:33.820
to the fake news question,
which is are you perceiving

01:16:33.820 --> 01:16:36.940
that expertise is
more discredited now

01:16:36.940 --> 01:16:38.380
or taken less seriously?

01:16:38.380 --> 01:16:40.090
I'm asking for a
particular reason.

01:16:40.090 --> 01:16:43.124
I was in a social situation
about six months ago--

01:16:43.124 --> 01:16:45.790
and I work on the Middle East, I
specialize in the Middle East--

01:16:45.790 --> 01:16:49.960
and I was absolutely shocked
at how many statements

01:16:49.960 --> 01:16:52.119
were made that were
completely wrong about Islam

01:16:52.119 --> 01:16:52.910
in the Middle East.

01:16:52.910 --> 01:16:55.210
So I got it in my head
to write this book aimed

01:16:55.210 --> 01:16:59.170
at the general public correcting
some of this misinformation.

01:16:59.170 --> 01:17:01.180
And I actually gave
up the idea because I

01:17:01.180 --> 01:17:03.220
became convinced
after conversations

01:17:03.220 --> 01:17:07.510
with colleagues that
my expertise would not

01:17:07.510 --> 01:17:10.780
be taken seriously by precisely
the people I want to target.

01:17:10.780 --> 01:17:12.970
And so I've been
sort of wrestling

01:17:12.970 --> 01:17:15.010
with whether it's
worth bothering

01:17:15.010 --> 01:17:17.155
with this sort of thing
and also whether--

01:17:17.155 --> 01:17:18.640
and this relates
to Naomi's point

01:17:18.640 --> 01:17:22.000
about where we place our pieces.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:24.640
If I'm writing something
about how Muslims

01:17:24.640 --> 01:17:26.530
do not actually
disproportionately blow

01:17:26.530 --> 01:17:29.280
themselves up or
something like that.

01:17:29.280 --> 01:17:32.500
Is this better
pitched at an outlet

01:17:32.500 --> 01:17:34.615
that's not The New York
Times or The Boston Globe

01:17:34.615 --> 01:17:37.240
or something like that so that
I reach a more general audience?

01:17:37.240 --> 01:17:42.072
Or is my likelihood of getting
discredited higher elsewhere?

01:17:42.072 --> 01:17:43.327
Thank you.

01:17:43.327 --> 01:17:44.785
JAMES DAO: That's
a tough question.

01:17:44.785 --> 01:17:45.280
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: I know.

01:17:45.280 --> 01:17:47.830
I think you've kind of put
your finger on the larger

01:17:47.830 --> 01:17:52.150
existential question that
our industry is really

01:17:52.150 --> 01:17:55.960
doing some soul
searching on right now.

01:17:55.960 --> 01:17:59.260
I think that if you're placing
something with The Boston

01:17:59.260 --> 01:18:01.146
Globe, you sort of
know the audience that

01:18:01.146 --> 01:18:02.770
is going to be reading
The Boston Globe

01:18:02.770 --> 01:18:05.410
or The New York
Times going into it.

01:18:05.410 --> 01:18:07.150
I would love to
say that you should

01:18:07.150 --> 01:18:09.850
be broader in your
thinking in terms

01:18:09.850 --> 01:18:12.984
of where you're placing things.

01:18:12.984 --> 01:18:15.400
I think that one of the issues
we saw in the last election

01:18:15.400 --> 01:18:18.940
is the fact that we have seen
the erosion of news outlets,

01:18:18.940 --> 01:18:21.430
particularly in the middle
part of the country,

01:18:21.430 --> 01:18:23.290
given the financial
circumstances

01:18:23.290 --> 01:18:24.940
that our industry finds itself.

01:18:24.940 --> 01:18:28.420
That said, you are
opening yourself up.

01:18:28.420 --> 01:18:32.055
I actually often feel
like I'm a therapist as

01:18:32.055 --> 01:18:33.430
much as anything
when I'm dealing

01:18:33.430 --> 01:18:35.134
with particularly new writers.

01:18:35.134 --> 01:18:36.550
And I have to
explain, like you're

01:18:36.550 --> 01:18:37.810
putting yourself on a page.

01:18:37.810 --> 01:18:41.740
We had a piece that a writer,
an academic at Berkeley

01:18:41.740 --> 01:18:44.350
wrote for us about
sexual assault

01:18:44.350 --> 01:18:46.780
and her own personal
experiences with it.

01:18:46.780 --> 01:18:49.670
And I literally had to--

01:18:49.670 --> 01:18:52.480
I went back and forth with
her repeatedly about the fact

01:18:52.480 --> 01:18:55.360
that she was really putting
her own personal experiences

01:18:55.360 --> 01:18:59.830
for the world to read and then
the comments were horrific.

01:18:59.830 --> 01:19:04.270
And I felt like we had done
a lot of work to prepare her

01:19:04.270 --> 01:19:06.010
for that I just didn't--

01:19:06.010 --> 01:19:07.776
that she was very upset.

01:19:07.776 --> 01:19:10.150
And so I feel like that that's
the one thing I always say

01:19:10.150 --> 01:19:12.580
is make sure you know what
you're getting into, too, when

01:19:12.580 --> 01:19:14.330
you're offering your
opinion, particularly

01:19:14.330 --> 01:19:17.410
on a controversial subject,
that you know going into it

01:19:17.410 --> 01:19:19.850
there are going to be people
who disagree with you.

01:19:19.850 --> 01:19:21.360
NAOMI ORESKES: I don't think
you should give up, though.

01:19:21.360 --> 01:19:22.485
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: No, no.

01:19:22.485 --> 01:19:25.009
NAOMI ORESKES: I think,
actually, the harder it is,

01:19:25.009 --> 01:19:26.050
the more important it is.

01:19:26.050 --> 01:19:26.905
Right?

01:19:26.905 --> 01:19:27.004
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Yeah.

01:19:27.004 --> 01:19:27.400
It's a good point.

01:19:27.400 --> 01:19:28.420
NAOMI ORESKES: And
I think there are

01:19:28.420 --> 01:19:29.961
things you can do
to protect yourself

01:19:29.961 --> 01:19:33.250
and maybe we should have
another session for us academics

01:19:33.250 --> 01:19:35.050
to talk about how
to protect yourself,

01:19:35.050 --> 01:19:36.550
because I'm trying
to figure out how

01:19:36.550 --> 01:19:38.650
come my name got taken
off that list of the 40

01:19:38.650 --> 01:19:40.952
horrible liberal professors--

01:19:40.952 --> 01:19:42.160
anyway, that's another story.

01:19:42.160 --> 01:19:45.190
But there are a lot of
people in this country who

01:19:45.190 --> 01:19:46.570
want to hear what
you have to say

01:19:46.570 --> 01:19:48.610
and the trick is to figure
out how to reach them

01:19:48.610 --> 01:19:49.900
and that means working
with your editor

01:19:49.900 --> 01:19:50.983
to think about strategies.

01:19:50.983 --> 01:19:53.320
And one thing I learned
after my last book

01:19:53.320 --> 01:19:56.530
that I'm taking forward
into my next project--

01:19:56.530 --> 01:20:00.200
and this gets back to the whole
fly over country problem--

01:20:00.200 --> 01:20:01.240
I hate that expression.

01:20:01.240 --> 01:20:05.980
But most book editors, like
most newspaper editors,

01:20:05.980 --> 01:20:09.320
are very focused on certain
populations in New York,

01:20:09.320 --> 01:20:10.820
Boston, Los Angeles,
San Francisco,

01:20:10.820 --> 01:20:12.820
people who buy books,
people who buy newspapers,

01:20:12.820 --> 01:20:15.400
people who still subscribe to
newspapers, and that's great

01:20:15.400 --> 01:20:17.985
and those people are important
and we are those people.

01:20:17.985 --> 01:20:20.110
But there are a lot of
other people in other places

01:20:20.110 --> 01:20:23.740
who will buy books and read
books if you reach out to them,

01:20:23.740 --> 01:20:25.459
but your editor
won't send you them

01:20:25.459 --> 01:20:27.250
because your editor's
business model is not

01:20:27.250 --> 01:20:29.310
based on Des Moines--

01:20:29.310 --> 01:20:30.490
I keep coming back to Iowa.

01:20:30.490 --> 01:20:32.750
I was obviously out
of my mind right now.

01:20:32.750 --> 01:20:34.630
But you can negotiate
with your editor.

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:36.910
And I learned this in
my last book project

01:20:36.910 --> 01:20:38.740
because my editor was
just going to send me

01:20:38.740 --> 01:20:41.830
to five big cities,
urban markets,

01:20:41.830 --> 01:20:44.230
but people reached out to
me and I went on a book tour

01:20:44.230 --> 01:20:44.890
in Kansas.

01:20:44.890 --> 01:20:46.620
I went to three
cities in Kansas--

01:20:46.620 --> 01:20:48.394
Lawrence, Hays, and Manhattan.

01:20:48.394 --> 01:20:50.560
It was one of the best
things I ever did in my life.

01:20:50.560 --> 01:20:53.050
And to this day, I
carry with me the woman

01:20:53.050 --> 01:20:54.820
I met in Hays, Kansas.

01:20:54.820 --> 01:20:57.670
So I went to Hays, Kansas
to talk about climate change

01:20:57.670 --> 01:21:01.240
in a very, very, very red place
surrounded by wheat fields

01:21:01.240 --> 01:21:04.060
and this woman came up to me
and she said, God bless you

01:21:04.060 --> 01:21:06.280
for coming Hays.

01:21:06.280 --> 01:21:08.380
So I mean, you can
reach people, but you

01:21:08.380 --> 01:21:10.750
have to go to where
they are and there

01:21:10.750 --> 01:21:11.890
are strategies to do that.

01:21:11.890 --> 01:21:13.880
And I think we could
talk about that

01:21:13.880 --> 01:21:18.120
and I'd love to talk more
about that, actually.

01:21:18.120 --> 01:21:20.846
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Yes.

01:21:20.846 --> 01:21:23.220
AUDIENCE: I'm Tyler VanderWeele,
School of Public Health.

01:21:23.220 --> 01:21:25.680
I was wondering if any of
you had additional balm

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:27.570
to offer to the
paranoid academic who

01:21:27.570 --> 01:21:31.210
would like to keep in all of
the caveats and exceptions.

01:21:31.210 --> 01:21:36.420
I recently published an
Op-Ed on protective effects

01:21:36.420 --> 01:21:38.970
of religious
participation on health.

01:21:38.970 --> 01:21:42.990
And after the editor was done
with my carefully constructed

01:21:42.990 --> 01:21:45.240
piece, while I could
see how it was much more

01:21:45.240 --> 01:21:47.829
appealing to a general audience,
made me cringe a little bit.

01:21:47.829 --> 01:21:49.620
Is this something that
we just kind of need

01:21:49.620 --> 01:21:52.740
to deal with and get over or
do you have further advice you

01:21:52.740 --> 01:21:55.560
might give to those of
us who find ourselves

01:21:55.560 --> 01:21:56.765
in such a position?

01:21:56.765 --> 01:21:58.140
IRIS ADLER: I
think you just need

01:21:58.140 --> 01:22:00.450
to keep on focusing
on the impact

01:22:00.450 --> 01:22:03.510
that you're going to have by
getting your pieces published.

01:22:03.510 --> 01:22:07.800
that's the price that you're
paying in spite of the fact

01:22:07.800 --> 01:22:10.770
that it might be contrary
to all of your training

01:22:10.770 --> 01:22:12.264
and all of your instincts.

01:22:12.264 --> 01:22:13.680
And quite frankly,
that's why it's

01:22:13.680 --> 01:22:16.230
so hard to work with
academics because they

01:22:16.230 --> 01:22:22.032
know they hold and cherish these
sort of rules in their head

01:22:22.032 --> 01:22:23.490
about how they
should write and how

01:22:23.490 --> 01:22:25.500
they should express
them self very dearly,

01:22:25.500 --> 01:22:26.980
and it's understandable.

01:22:26.980 --> 01:22:28.620
That's how they've been trained.

01:22:28.620 --> 01:22:33.300
But you just have to think
of the greater impact

01:22:33.300 --> 01:22:35.610
that you will have by
sort of letting go of that

01:22:35.610 --> 01:22:37.050
and just suck it up and do it.

01:22:37.050 --> 01:22:38.740
[LAUGHTER]

01:22:38.740 --> 01:22:42.960
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: I want to
be clear to underscore that it's

01:22:42.960 --> 01:22:48.150
not an anti-intellectualism
or anything like that

01:22:48.150 --> 01:22:53.130
that motivates that
response from journalists.

01:22:53.130 --> 01:22:55.980
I spent nine years on
the Pulitzer Prize Board

01:22:55.980 --> 01:22:58.260
and for those books,
we spent a lot

01:22:58.260 --> 01:23:00.870
of time talking
about the footnotes

01:23:00.870 --> 01:23:04.860
because that was very
important to that form.

01:23:04.860 --> 01:23:09.630
It's a different form and it
has different conventions.

01:23:09.630 --> 01:23:14.910
So one is absolutely
essential for one form

01:23:14.910 --> 01:23:17.190
and a different
convention absolutely

01:23:17.190 --> 01:23:20.340
essential for building an
audience with the other form.

01:23:20.340 --> 01:23:23.175
So you just have to kind
of think of it that way

01:23:23.175 --> 01:23:24.130
and let go.

01:23:24.130 --> 01:23:26.640
IRIS ADLER: I think
it's also important

01:23:26.640 --> 01:23:30.030
that we really have hard
data now, all of us,

01:23:30.030 --> 01:23:32.940
on our online
writings and columns.

01:23:32.940 --> 01:23:35.820
When did people stop
reading, at what point?

01:23:35.820 --> 01:23:37.590
And we have it for
the radio, too.

01:23:37.590 --> 01:23:40.230
At what point did they stop
listening to that story?

01:23:40.230 --> 01:23:47.310
And it's not that we don't
want to go long and deep as you

01:23:47.310 --> 01:23:49.380
might want to, it's
just that we really

01:23:49.380 --> 01:23:52.500
understand with very hard
data that people are going

01:23:52.500 --> 01:23:55.310
to just stop paying attention.

01:23:55.310 --> 01:23:59.610
JAMES DAO: Ann Marie,
can I just say we all

01:23:59.610 --> 01:24:01.320
represent opinion
sections so we want

01:24:01.320 --> 01:24:03.528
you to have a point of view
and so that point of view

01:24:03.528 --> 01:24:05.880
has to be clear and
if it's not, you

01:24:05.880 --> 01:24:08.940
publish it in some other place.

01:24:08.940 --> 01:24:14.870
But that said, we often
want Op-Eds or long essays,

01:24:14.870 --> 01:24:18.665
whichever, to reflect you
know the counter argument

01:24:18.665 --> 01:24:21.270
and to the degree
you can explain

01:24:21.270 --> 01:24:23.880
what that counter-argument
is concisely

01:24:23.880 --> 01:24:27.780
and accurately, it makes for
a better piece, almost always.

01:24:27.780 --> 01:24:29.640
Of course, you're
setting it up accurately

01:24:29.640 --> 01:24:30.760
so you can knock it down.

01:24:30.760 --> 01:24:33.395
But that should be
part-- it doesn't

01:24:33.395 --> 01:24:34.770
have to be a part
of every Op-Ed,

01:24:34.770 --> 01:24:38.110
but that's often a part of
a very successful Op-Ed.

01:24:38.110 --> 01:24:39.610
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY:
Sorry, I'll just

01:24:39.610 --> 01:24:42.510
add, the one other thing I
would say is trust your editor,

01:24:42.510 --> 01:24:46.710
especially if you're working
with a reputable publication.

01:24:46.710 --> 01:24:49.350
You can push back if you
think, for instance, a headline

01:24:49.350 --> 01:24:53.689
goes too far or something,
but we do do this for a living

01:24:53.689 --> 01:24:55.980
and we do have a sense of
what people are going to read

01:24:55.980 --> 01:24:59.530
and what people are
going to respond to.

01:24:59.530 --> 01:25:04.720
And so I often get
pushback that how could

01:25:04.720 --> 01:25:09.690
I possibly choose to take this
paragraph out, it's essential.

01:25:09.690 --> 01:25:13.390
But there is actually thinking
behind why we're doing that.

01:25:15.796 --> 01:25:17.920
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: Does
anyone have a question who

01:25:17.920 --> 01:25:20.470
hasn't asked a question first?

01:25:20.470 --> 01:25:21.020
No?

01:25:21.020 --> 01:25:21.520
OK.

01:25:21.520 --> 01:25:22.984
Go ahead.

01:25:22.984 --> 01:25:24.650
AUDIENCE: This is
just a quick follow up

01:25:24.650 --> 01:25:26.149
to what the gentleman
asked earlier.

01:25:26.149 --> 01:25:28.160
So I've had great experiences
with most editors.

01:25:28.160 --> 01:25:30.470
On rare occasion, I
come across an editor

01:25:30.470 --> 01:25:35.052
who has really taken what
they've gotten from me

01:25:35.052 --> 01:25:37.010
and used it to convey a
very different message.

01:25:37.010 --> 01:25:40.610
So at what point does my
ownership over those ideas

01:25:40.610 --> 01:25:42.590
begin and so on?

01:25:42.590 --> 01:25:44.720
And is it appropriate for
me to say, sorry, I don't

01:25:44.720 --> 01:25:45.400
want to be a part of this?

01:25:45.400 --> 01:25:46.100
JAMES DAO: Yeah, totally.

01:25:46.100 --> 01:25:46.490
Absolutely.

01:25:46.490 --> 01:25:47.781
KATHLEEN KINGSBURY: Absolutely.

01:25:50.190 --> 01:25:53.270
JAMES DAO: We view-- and if this
was a New York Times editor,

01:25:53.270 --> 01:25:55.970
you let me know-- we view our
role as helping you to make

01:25:55.970 --> 01:25:58.400
your argument, not to make our--

01:25:58.400 --> 01:26:01.790
most of us, we're running pieces
regularly that have arguments

01:26:01.790 --> 01:26:06.470
that we think are daft or
terrible or wrong headed,

01:26:06.470 --> 01:26:08.120
but that's what we do.

01:26:08.120 --> 01:26:09.460
That's what the Op-Ed is.

01:26:09.460 --> 01:26:11.460
That's the Op in
Op-Ed, to some degree.

01:26:11.460 --> 01:26:15.000
So you should always--

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:16.670
it is your piece.

01:26:16.670 --> 01:26:19.710
If you don't like where it's
going, then you pull it.

01:26:19.710 --> 01:26:20.990
If it's right on deadline.

01:26:20.990 --> 01:26:22.810
I may not use you again, but--

01:26:22.810 --> 01:26:23.840
I'm kidding.

01:26:23.840 --> 01:26:29.330
But we always send playbacks
of the edited versions and very

01:26:29.330 --> 01:26:32.480
often people pitch a fit at the
last minute and we try to work

01:26:32.480 --> 01:26:34.682
out a compromise,
and if we can't--

01:26:34.682 --> 01:26:36.140
it's never happened
under my watch,

01:26:36.140 --> 01:26:39.110
but I'm sure there's been cases
where people pull their pieces.

01:26:39.110 --> 01:26:39.950
NAOMI ORESKES: I
have to go to class,

01:26:39.950 --> 01:26:42.491
but I wanted to just add because
this is so important for you

01:26:42.491 --> 01:26:45.140
guys on the supply side.

01:26:45.140 --> 01:26:47.105
That does happen and I've
had great experiences

01:26:47.105 --> 01:26:48.980
with almost all the
editors I've worked with,

01:26:48.980 --> 01:26:49.979
learned a lot from them.

01:26:49.979 --> 01:26:52.280
Totally agree like your
editor is an expert

01:26:52.280 --> 01:26:54.230
and you should trust
them, but I recently

01:26:54.230 --> 01:26:56.060
did have an experience
with a piece that

01:26:56.060 --> 01:26:58.370
had gone back and forth,
worked closely with an editor.

01:26:58.370 --> 01:27:01.300
I was happy, he was
happy, all good.

01:27:01.300 --> 01:27:03.320
And at the 11th hour,
I mean literally,

01:27:03.320 --> 01:27:06.890
like 11 o'clock at night on the
night before this was supposed

01:27:06.890 --> 01:27:09.920
to run, he came back with a
change that had been suggested

01:27:09.920 --> 01:27:11.480
by his boss--

01:27:11.480 --> 01:27:13.100
we won't say what
newspaper it was--

01:27:13.100 --> 01:27:15.260
and it was unacceptable to me.

01:27:15.260 --> 01:27:18.390
And I was actually very shocked
and I said to this editor

01:27:18.390 --> 01:27:19.640
who I had a relationship with.

01:27:19.640 --> 01:27:23.960
I said you can't be serious.

01:27:23.960 --> 01:27:26.829
Actually, to my mind,
completely undermined

01:27:26.829 --> 01:27:28.370
in a significant
way what I was doing

01:27:28.370 --> 01:27:30.140
and I just said
it's not acceptable.

01:27:30.140 --> 01:27:34.190
I said either we get is that
or I'm pulling the piece.

01:27:34.190 --> 01:27:36.500
And at that point, you have
leverage because they've

01:27:36.500 --> 01:27:37.760
actually made a space.

01:27:37.760 --> 01:27:39.470
Not that they don't have other
things they could put in,

01:27:39.470 --> 01:27:41.390
of course, I'm sure you
have tons of things.

01:27:41.390 --> 01:27:42.560
JAMES DAO: We've learned
our lesson on that.

01:27:42.560 --> 01:27:42.710
Yeah.

01:27:42.710 --> 01:27:44.660
NAOMI ORESKES: But the point
is it wasn't acceptable

01:27:44.660 --> 01:27:46.110
and I just said
it's not acceptable.

01:27:46.110 --> 01:27:48.110
And then we went back and
forth a few more times

01:27:48.110 --> 01:27:49.970
and came up with a
compromise that was.

01:27:49.970 --> 01:27:52.190
So you have leverage,
especially at that last moment

01:27:52.190 --> 01:27:55.700
and you shouldn't allow
anything to go forward that--

01:27:55.700 --> 01:27:57.480
I mean, stylistic
things are one thing,

01:27:57.480 --> 01:27:59.150
but if there's something
substantive that you are not

01:27:59.150 --> 01:28:00.770
comfortable with,
you actually have

01:28:00.770 --> 01:28:03.020
to stop it because
that's your expertise

01:28:03.020 --> 01:28:04.340
and credibility on the line.

01:28:04.340 --> 01:28:06.589
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI: And the
last thing an editor wants

01:28:06.589 --> 01:28:09.979
is the person who wrote the
piece complaining publicly

01:28:09.979 --> 01:28:12.020
about how something was
distorted in their piece.

01:28:12.020 --> 01:28:14.120
So it's just in
everybody's interest.

01:28:14.120 --> 01:28:15.800
And before we let
Naomi go, there

01:28:15.800 --> 01:28:17.752
is one point I
wanted to bring up

01:28:17.752 --> 01:28:19.460
that maybe she could
just quickly address

01:28:19.460 --> 01:28:21.830
before she goes to class.

01:28:21.830 --> 01:28:25.610
And that is I think I've
heard from, in particular,

01:28:25.610 --> 01:28:28.910
from junior faculty, that it's
very hard sometimes to think

01:28:28.910 --> 01:28:32.300
about and to justify why
they should be spending time

01:28:32.300 --> 01:28:35.150
doing this kind of
public work when they're

01:28:35.150 --> 01:28:38.780
so busy doing the work they
need to do to achieve tenure

01:28:38.780 --> 01:28:41.352
or some other status--

01:28:41.352 --> 01:28:42.185
NAOMI ORESKES: Yeah.

01:28:42.185 --> 01:28:43.934
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
--and focus third time

01:28:43.934 --> 01:28:45.240
on academic publishing.

01:28:45.240 --> 01:28:47.990
And so I'm wondering
if you could just,

01:28:47.990 --> 01:28:53.630
from a point of empathy, just
talk about that for a minute.

01:28:53.630 --> 01:28:56.030
What is the value of
doing this work when

01:28:56.030 --> 01:28:58.497
you've got so much else to do?

01:28:58.497 --> 01:28:59.330
NAOMI ORESKES: Yeah.

01:28:59.330 --> 01:29:01.400
That's a hard one
because I never

01:29:01.400 --> 01:29:03.381
like to tell other
people what to do

01:29:03.381 --> 01:29:05.630
or how to live their lives,
but in terms of the value,

01:29:05.630 --> 01:29:07.770
I think that's a good way
of putting the question.

01:29:07.770 --> 01:29:10.682
I think there's a
couple of things.

01:29:10.682 --> 01:29:12.140
I think this election
really brings

01:29:12.140 --> 01:29:15.077
home in a really serious way--

01:29:15.077 --> 01:29:16.910
a lot of people are
beating up on themselves

01:29:16.910 --> 01:29:18.650
about the election
and different things

01:29:18.650 --> 01:29:20.560
they could or should have done.

01:29:20.560 --> 01:29:22.359
And all I know is I
sleep well at night

01:29:22.359 --> 01:29:23.900
because I know for
the last 15 years,

01:29:23.900 --> 01:29:26.420
I've been doing everything
possible that I can

01:29:26.420 --> 01:29:28.499
from my vantage
point to communicate

01:29:28.499 --> 01:29:30.290
to the American people
about climate change

01:29:30.290 --> 01:29:31.623
and why it matters to our lives.

01:29:31.623 --> 01:29:35.060
So I sleep well at night
knowing that I've done my part

01:29:35.060 --> 01:29:37.520
and that's, for me,
personally gigantic.

01:29:37.520 --> 01:29:41.060
And I couldn't justify being
an ivory tower academic

01:29:41.060 --> 01:29:43.359
if I didn't personally
have that piece of my life.

01:29:43.359 --> 01:29:44.900
So it's just a really
personal thing.

01:29:44.900 --> 01:29:47.510
Other people will
feel differently.

01:29:47.510 --> 01:29:50.540
On a less personal
note, I think the value

01:29:50.540 --> 01:29:52.880
from a sort of
pragmatic standpoint

01:29:52.880 --> 01:29:55.730
is that you actually do become
a better writer and better

01:29:55.730 --> 01:29:57.740
communicator when you
work with professionals

01:29:57.740 --> 01:29:59.210
like these amazing people here.

01:29:59.210 --> 01:30:02.030
This is my chance to suck up
to these wonderful people who

01:30:02.030 --> 01:30:05.270
have taken the time to
come to be with us today.

01:30:05.270 --> 01:30:08.270
Just like you want people
to respect your expertise,

01:30:08.270 --> 01:30:09.450
they have expertise.

01:30:09.450 --> 01:30:13.200
Like Iris just said, they
have data at their fingertips.

01:30:13.200 --> 01:30:14.075
They have experience.

01:30:14.075 --> 01:30:16.102
They know a lot
about what works.

01:30:16.102 --> 01:30:18.560
And when you work with them,
you learn from their expertise

01:30:18.560 --> 01:30:21.320
and you become a better
writer and that carries over

01:30:21.320 --> 01:30:23.210
into your teaching
and makes you better

01:30:23.210 --> 01:30:26.372
able to reach your students, it
carries over into your pitches

01:30:26.372 --> 01:30:28.580
to publishers when you're
shopping those books around

01:30:28.580 --> 01:30:30.230
and your publisher
asks, well, who's

01:30:30.230 --> 01:30:33.080
going to read this other than
the 17 experts in Sanskrit

01:30:33.080 --> 01:30:34.590
irregular verbs?

01:30:34.590 --> 01:30:35.090
Right?

01:30:35.090 --> 01:30:38.030
You have to make the
case for your work

01:30:38.030 --> 01:30:41.312
on all kinds of
different levels--

01:30:41.312 --> 01:30:43.020
well, Liz isn't at
Harvard Press anymore,

01:30:43.020 --> 01:30:45.050
but when you go to the
editor at Harvard Press.

01:30:45.050 --> 01:30:47.780
So being able to make
that pitch to boil it down

01:30:47.780 --> 01:30:52.730
to say why somebody should take
the time to read my 800 page

01:30:52.730 --> 01:30:55.670
magnum ocean opus on the
history of cold war oceans.

01:30:58.580 --> 01:31:01.670
I'm much more able to
sell my academic work

01:31:01.670 --> 01:31:05.650
as a result of having
done this more broader--

01:31:05.650 --> 01:31:07.400
I don't like to call
popular broader work.

01:31:07.400 --> 01:31:11.540
So I think it does make you
better at your job, overall.

01:31:11.540 --> 01:31:14.680
That doesn't happen
overnight, but it does happen.

01:31:14.680 --> 01:31:17.150
And I know when I work
with my students now,

01:31:17.150 --> 01:31:19.790
Jeff will tell you, I'm always
hitting on my students now,

01:31:19.790 --> 01:31:20.820
what is the point here?

01:31:20.820 --> 01:31:22.670
Why is this important?

01:31:22.670 --> 01:31:25.760
Why Should your reader
now spend the next three

01:31:25.760 --> 01:31:27.590
days of his or her
life reading this book?

01:31:27.590 --> 01:31:28.280
Right?

01:31:28.280 --> 01:31:30.570
And that carries over
to everything you do.

01:31:30.570 --> 01:31:33.820
So I think that's the
pragmatic value answer.

01:31:33.820 --> 01:31:35.570
ANN MARIE LIPINSKI:
That's a great answer.

01:31:35.570 --> 01:31:38.450
Thank you very much.

01:31:38.450 --> 01:31:42.930
I started by saying it was a
kind of a different time when

01:31:42.930 --> 01:31:46.460
Judy first put this together
and a lot has changed

01:31:46.460 --> 01:31:48.510
in the months since then.

01:31:48.510 --> 01:31:51.050
And the discussion here that
came up a couple of times

01:31:51.050 --> 01:31:56.630
about fake news
is really a huge--

01:31:56.630 --> 01:31:59.800
not so much development,
because it had been happening,

01:31:59.800 --> 01:32:04.220
but a moment and a moment
for all of us to acknowledge.

01:32:04.220 --> 01:32:10.820
And trust me, it's rocked our
industry in really significant

01:32:10.820 --> 01:32:18.260
ways as well as the tech and
the social industry that is also

01:32:18.260 --> 01:32:20.300
grappling with these issues.

01:32:20.300 --> 01:32:24.380
But the cure for fake
news is factual news.

01:32:24.380 --> 01:32:26.840
The cure for lies is knowledge.

01:32:26.840 --> 01:32:31.850
And it is so
incredibly important

01:32:31.850 --> 01:32:34.040
that you all think
about what role

01:32:34.040 --> 01:32:37.550
you can play in that, at least
it is from my perspective.

01:32:37.550 --> 01:32:40.820
And I'm in a completely
share Naomi's view

01:32:40.820 --> 01:32:42.710
of the value of that.

01:32:42.710 --> 01:32:48.180
So really on behalf
of the democracy,

01:32:48.180 --> 01:32:55.010
to thank you all who have so
much knowledge and expertise,

01:32:55.010 --> 01:32:57.410
to thank you all for taking
the time to even think

01:32:57.410 --> 01:33:00.170
about this issue
and how you might

01:33:00.170 --> 01:33:07.520
bring your voice to the
public in a stronger way.

01:33:07.520 --> 01:33:10.610
And then, please join
me before we break

01:33:10.610 --> 01:33:13.340
and let you talk to them
individually, if you'd like,

01:33:13.340 --> 01:33:16.850
please join me in thanking
our three amazing panelists

01:33:16.850 --> 01:33:18.050
for their time.

01:33:18.050 --> 01:33:20.800
[APPLAUSE]

